# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cobol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cobol/110-film] The film is fully housed in a plastic cartridge, which also registers the image when the film is advanced.
[src:cobol/110-film] There is a continuous backing paper, and the frame number is visible through a window at the rear of the cartridge.
[src:cobol/110-film] The film does not need to be rewound and is very simple to load and unload.
[src:cobol/110-film] The film is usually pre-exposed with frame lines and numbers, a feature intended to make it easier and more efficient for photo finishers to print.
[src:cobol/110-film] Unlike later competing formats, such as disc and APS film, processed 110 negatives are returned in strips, without the original cartridge.
[src:cobol/110-film] The 110 cartridge was introduced by Kodak in 1972 with Kodak Pocket Instamatic cameras with Kodachrome-X, Ektachrome-X, Kodacolor II, and Verichrome Pan film.
[src:cobol/110-film] The new pocket-sized cameras became immediately popular, and soon displaced competing subminiature cameras, such as the Minolta 16 series, from the market.
[src:cobol/110-film] The 16 mm film width allowed Kodachrome film in 110 size to be processed on the existing processing machines that processed movie films in the Standard 8 mm film and 16 mm film sizes.
[src:cobol/110-film] Fujifilm stopped manufacturing 110 format film in September 2009.
[src:cobol/110-film] Lomography re-commenced 110 film production in 2011.
[src:cobol/110-film] As of 2024, they offer 110 Black and White, Color Negative, and a variety of experimental stocks such as Lomochrome Purple and Metropolis.
[src:cobol/110-film] Estes Industries has long marketed several model rockets, the most notable being the Astrocam, with a simple 110 camera in the nose; the shutter is triggered when the nose cone separates from the rocket body.
[src:cobol/110-film] Tyco (in their Spy Tech line of toys) made two toy spy cameras in the early 1990s that utilized 110 film, called the Hidden Camera and Reese's Camera.
[src:cobol/110-film] The Hidden Camera had a periscope-like attachment that used a mirror for taking pictures around corners or behind objects.
[src:cobol/110-film] The Hidden Camera's shape and size is similar to that of the Minox B.
[src:cobol/110-film] The only new 110 film available on the market is currently produced by Austrian analogue photography company Lomography.
[src:cobol/110-film] Such cameras are capable of making high-quality images on 110 film.
[src:cobol/110-film] Some of these cameras are quite small and still hold appeal to subminiature-photography enthusiasts.
[src:cobol/110-film] The small negative size of 110 film makes it difficult to enlarge successfully.
[src:cobol/110-film] For these reasons, the 110 format is associated with prints that are often rather grainy and unsharp.
[src:cobol/110-film] This has led to the misconception that the cartridge itself is incapable of holding film flat enough for making high-quality negatives.
[src:cobol/110-film] The 110 cartridge, as specified by Kodak, has a plastic tab on one end.
[src:cobol/110-film] Camera designers had the option of using this tab to sense film speed, enabling sophisticated cameras to switch between high- and low-speed film.
[src:cobol/110-film] A short tab indicated high-speed film, and a long tab indicated low-speed film.
[src:cobol/110-film] Kodak left it to the film manufacturer to decide which film speeds were high or low.
[src:cobol/110-film] Only a few cameras took advantage of this feature: Rollei A110, Canon 110 ED 20, Minolta 110 Zoom SLR Mark I/II, Minox 110S, Voigtlander Vitoret 110 EL, Pentax Auto 110 and the Kodak Ektralite 10.
[src:cobol/110-film] Some manufacturers would vary the low speed ASA setting and then change it in later models.
[src:cobol/110-film] For example, Minox 110S low speed was 64 ASA (Kodachrome then being made for 110) and high 400 ASA: but Canon 110 ED has 80 ASA only, with the 110 ED 20 having 80 and 400 ASA.
[src:cobol/110-film] The last 110 film that Kodak produced was ISO 400 speed packed in a cartridge that senses as "low" speed.
[src:cobol/110-film] As shown in the photograph to the right, these cartridges can be modified by hand so that they signal the proper speed to the camera.
[src:cobol/110-film] Although the format is commonly associated with print film, Kodak also produced Kodachrome 64 slide film in 110 cartridges until 1982.
[src:cobol/110-film] In 2012 Lomography re-introduced slide film for 110 with their Peacock 200 ASA model.
[src:cobol/110-film] However, since not all 110 cameras have a settable ASA dial (low or high, depending on presence of a notch in the cassette), a neutral-density filter has to be used over the lens or the exposure compensation dial has to be used where available.
[src:cobol/110-film] Otherwise, over-exposure by a factor of x2 will result, leading to over-exposed images.
[src:cobol/110-film] Along with standard-sized slides that fit into standard projectors, 110 slide film could also be processed into smaller format slides.
[src:cobol/110-film] The latter requires special *Pocket Carousel* projectors, or the Leica 110 projector.
[src:cobol/110-film] Kodak's Verichrome Pan was the only 110 black and white film produced until 2012, when Lomography manufactured their "Orca" Black and White film at 100 ISO speed.
[src:cobol/110-film] This speed is supported by most 110 cameras.
[src:cobol/110-film] Lomography went on to launch color, redscale, and slide film cartridges which, along with black and white, are the only 110 film types in production as of 2022.
[src:cobol/126-film] Although 126 was once very popular, as of 2008 it is no longer manufactured, however, most photofinishers can process it using standard day load roll film cassettes.
[src:cobol/126-film] In 1963, Kodak introduced a new film, encased in a plastic cartridge, for which they re-introduced the "126" designation.
[src:cobol/126-film] (The number was originally used for the unrelated 126 roll film format from 1906 to 1949).
[src:cobol/126-film] The term "126" was intended to show that 26 mm square images were recorded, using Kodak's common 1xx film numbering system.
[src:cobol/126-film] However the image size is actually 28×28 mm, which usually was reduced to approximately 26.5×26.5 mm by masking during printing or mounting.
[src:cobol/126-film] At the nominal 28 mm square size, the image diagonal is 39.6 mm, which is close to the 43.3 mm diagonal of a 135 film frame (24×36 mm); the crop factor or equivalent focal length multiplier is 1.09 based on the diagonal measurements.
[src:cobol/126-film] The 126 film cartridge and format were defined in ISO 3029, which has since been withdrawn.
[src:cobol/126-film] Like the 120 format, there is a continuous backing paper, and the frame number is visible through a small window at the rear of the cartridge.
[src:cobol/126-film] Cameras for this type of film are equipped with a large rectangular window in the back door, through which is visible not only the frame number, but also a portion of the label showing the film type and speed.
[src:cobol/126-film] The cartridge has a captive take-up spool, but no supply spool: the film and backing paper are simply coiled tightly and placed in the supply end of the cartridge.
[src:cobol/126-film] The positioning of the image is fixed by the cartridge.
[src:cobol/126-film] The film is 35 mm wide, but unlike 135 film, it is unperforated, except for one registration hole per image, similar to the earlier 828 film.
[src:cobol/126-film] The camera is equipped with a sensing pin which falls into this hole when the film is fully advanced to the next frame, at which point the winding knob or lever is locked, so as to prevent winding past the pre-exposed frame lines.
[src:cobol/126-film] The top edge of the cartridge above the film gate has a square notch in a specific position that signaled the film speed.
[src:cobol/126-film] Some of the higher-end cameras used this notch to determine the correct exposure, or to set the light meter, if so equipped.
[src:cobol/126-film] Although the actual films manufactured in 126 cartridge format had speeds varying between ISO 64/19° and ISO 400/27°, the standard defined 20 different speeds, spanning from ISO 20/14° to ISO 1600/33°.
[src:cobol/126-film] The film was originally available in 12 and 20 image lengths; at the time regular production stopped it was only available in 24 exposure cartridges.
[src:cobol/126-film] The exposed film is stored on the take-up spool and does not need to be rewound, making the cameras very simple to load and unload.
[src:cobol/126-film] Kodak published instructions for assembling a simple pinhole camera using a 126 cartridge with typical household materials.
[src:cobol/126-film] The format was introduced in 1963 by Kodak under the brand name *Kodapak*, together with the Instamatic camera line.
[src:cobol/126-film] Around ten million cameras were made by Kodak and other companies.
[src:cobol/126-film] With a few exceptions, the format was mainly used for fairly simple amateur cameras; some of the few high-end models were manufactured by companies included Kodak, Minolta, Rollei, Yashica and Zeiss Ikon.
[src:cobol/126-film] The 126 cartridge also was used as the basis for a pinhole camera that could be built using household supplies.
[src:cobol/126-film] Kodak officially discontinued the format on 31 December 1999.
[src:cobol/126-film] Unused, outdated 126 films continue to show up at thrift stores, estate sales, and online auctions.
[src:cobol/126-film] Unless they have been stored frozen, they are probably deteriorated and are suitable only for experimenting.
[src:cobol/126-film] Ferrania in Italy was the last factory producing 126 film.
[src:cobol/126-film] They marketed an ISO 200 color print film under their *Solaris* brand.
[src:cobol/126-film] The last scheduled production run took place in April 2007, but an unscheduled production run in late 2007 surprised industry observers and raised hopes that it had not actually been discontinued.
[src:cobol/126-film] Ferrania's subsequent bankruptcy meant that there was no longer any large-scale factory source for 126 film.
[src:cobol/126-film] Some photographers reuse the plastic cartridge from outdated 126 films and reload them with fresh 35mm film.
[src:cobol/126-film] The process is not difficult, but it is not entirely practical since the process must be carried out in the dark, as the 35mm film must be removed from the cartridge.
[src:cobol/126-film] In addition, the two films have significantly different perforation schemes.
[src:cobol/126-film] 126 cameras have a film-advance mechanism that relies on one edge perforation per image, and 35mm camera film has eight perforations per image, on both edges of the film.
[src:cobol/126-film] The photographer must use the film-advance mechanism several times between images, and one edge of each image will have visible perforations.
[src:cobol/126-film] An adapter is available for photographers without access to 126 cartridges, but the adapter does not fit all cameras.
[src:cobol/126-film] Because it is 35 mm wide and is developed in industry-standard C-41 process chemistry, processing of most 126 films is readily available, as long as the photofinisher knows that it is standard, 35 mm-wide, C-41 film.
[src:cobol/126-film] Printing the photos can present problems, because modern film processing equipment often cannot handle the square format of 126 film.
[src:cobol/126-film] Some specialist photographic printers can correctly handle it.
[src:cobol/126-film] Standard flatbed scanners that have a light source for scanning film can be used to scan 126 negatives, perhaps using a mask made with black paper.
[src:cobol/126-film] Note that older film may require uncommon film processing such as C-22.
[src:cobol/135-film] The term 135 was introduced by Kodak in 1934 as a designation for 35 mm film specifically for still photography, perforated with Kodak Standard perforations.
[src:cobol/135-film] It quickly grew in popularity, surpassing 120 film by the late 1960s to become the most popular photographic film size.
[src:cobol/135-film] Despite competition from formats such as 120, 828, 126, 110, and APS, it remains the most popular film size today.
[src:cobol/135-film] The size of the 135 film frame with its frame's aspect ratio of 2:3 has been adopted by many high-end digital single-lens reflex and digital mirrorless cameras, commonly referred to as "full frame".
[src:cobol/135-film] Even though the format is much smaller than historical medium format and large format film, being historically referred to as *miniature format* or *small format*, it is much larger than image sensors in most compact cameras and smartphone cameras.
[src:cobol/135-film] The engineering standard for this film is controlled by ISO 1007 titled '135-size film and magazine'.
[src:cobol/135-film] The 135 film size is derived from earlier still cameras using lengths of 35 mm movie film, which had the same size but with different perforations.
[src:cobol/135-film] The 35 mm film standard for motion picture film was established in Thomas Edison's lab by William Kennedy Laurie Dickson.
[src:cobol/135-film] Dickson took 70 mm film stock supplied by George Eastman's Eastman Kodak Company.
[src:cobol/135-film] The 70 mm film was cut lengthwise into two equal width (35 mm) strips, spliced together end to end, and then perforated along both edges.
[src:cobol/135-film] The original picture size was 18×24 mm (half the full frame size later used in still photography).
[src:cobol/135-film] There were four perforations on each side of a motion picture frame.
[src:cobol/135-film] While the Leica camera popularized the format, several 35 mm still cameras used perforated movie film before the Leica was introduced in the 1920s.
[src:cobol/135-film] The first patent for one was issued to Leo, Audobard, and Baradat in England in 1908.
[src:cobol/135-film] The first full-scale production camera was the Homéos, a stereo camera produced by Jules Richard in 1913 and sold until 1920.
[src:cobol/135-film] It took 18x24 mm stereo pairs and used two Tessar lenses.
[src:cobol/135-film] In 1909, the French Étienne Mollier designed a device for small-format photography, the "Cent-Vues", which used the 35 mm perforated film to take consecutive hundred views in 18×24 mm.
[src:cobol/135-film] He manufactured it, won the gold medal in the Concours Lépine, and in 1910 sold at a small scale and without much success.
[src:cobol/135-film] The first big-selling 35 mm still camera was the American Tourist Multiple, which also appeared in 1913, at a cost of $175 (~5,600 US Dollars in 2024) The first camera to take full-frame 24×36 mm exposures seems to be the Simplex, introduced in the U.S. in 1914.
[src:cobol/135-film] It took either 800 half-frame or 400 full-frame shots on 50 ft (15.2 m) rolls.
[src:cobol/135-film] The Minigraph, by Levy-Roth of Berlin, another half-frame small camera was sold in Germany in 1915.
[src:cobol/135-film] The patent for the Debrie Sept camera, a combination 35 mm still and movie camera was issued in 1918; the camera sold from 1922.
[src:cobol/135-film] The Furet camera made and sold in France in 1923 took full-frame 24x36 mm negatives, and was the first cheap small 35 mm camera of similar appearance to more modern models.
[src:cobol/135-film] The Leica Camera designed by Oskar Barnack used 35 mm film, and proved that a format as small as 24 mm × 36 mm was suitable for professional photography.
[src:cobol/135-film] Although Barnack designed his prototype camera around 1913, the first experimental production run of ur-Leicas (Serial No.
[src:cobol/135-film] Full-scale production of the Leica did not begin until 1925.
[src:cobol/135-film] While by that time, there were at least a dozen other 35 mm cameras available, the Leica was a success.
[src:cobol/135-film] It came to be associated with the format, mostly because of this 35 mm popularity, as well as the entire company legacy.
[src:cobol/135-film] Early Leica cameras are considered highly collectable items.
[src:cobol/135-film] The original Leica prototype holds the record as being the world's most expensive camera, selling for €2.16 million in 2012.
[src:cobol/135-film] In the earliest days, the photographer had to load the film into reusable cassettes and, at least for some cameras, cut the film leader.
[src:cobol/135-film] In 1934, Kodak introduced a *135* daylight-loading single-use cassette.
[src:cobol/135-film] This cassette was engineered so that it could be used in both Leica and Zeiss Ikon Contax cameras along with the camera for which it was invented, namely the Kodak Retina camera.
[src:cobol/135-film] The Retina camera and this daylight loading cassette were the invention of Dr.
[src:cobol/135-film] August Nagel's company in December, 1931, and began marketing the *Kodak Retina* in the summer of 1934.
[src:cobol/135-film] The first Kodak Retina camera was a Typ 117.
[src:cobol/135-film] The 35 mm Kodak Retina camera line remained in production until 1969.
[src:cobol/135-film] Kodak also introduced a line of American made cameras that were simpler and more economical than the Retina.
[src:cobol/135-film] Argus, too, made a long-lived range of 35 mm cameras; notably the Argus C3.
[src:cobol/135-film] Kodak launched 135-format Kodachrome colour film in 1936.
[src:cobol/135-film] AGFA followed with the introduction of *Agfacolor Neu* later in the same year.
[src:cobol/135-film] The designations *235* and *435* refer to 35 mm film in daylight-loading spools, that could be loaded into Contax or Leica style reusable cassettes, respectively, without need of a darkroom.
[src:cobol/135-film] The *335* was a daylight loading spool for the 24 × 23 mm stereo format.
[src:cobol/135-film] Reflex viewfinders, both twin-and single-lens, had been used with earlier cameras using plates and rollfilm.
[src:cobol/135-film] The first 35 mm single-lens reflex (SLR) was the Kine Exakta, introduced in 1936.
[src:cobol/135-film] World War II interrupted development of the type.
[src:cobol/135-film] After the war, Exakta resumed development and the Contax S model with the now familiar pentaprism viewing feature was introduced in 1949.
[src:cobol/135-film] In the 1950s, the SLR also began to be produced in Japan by such companies as Asahi and Miranda.
[src:cobol/135-film] Asahi's Pentax introduced the instant-return mirror, important for the popularity of SLRs; until then, the viewfinder on an SLR camera blanked as the mirror sprang out of the optical path just before taking the picture, returning when the film was wound on.
[src:cobol/135-film] Nikon's F model, introduced in March 1959, was a system camera that greatly improved the quality and utility of 35 mm format cameras, encouraging professionals (especially photojournalists) to switch from larger format cameras to the versatile, rugged, and fast SLR design.
[src:cobol/135-film] Numerous other film formats waxed and waned in popularity, but by the 1970s, interchangeable-lens SLR cameras and smaller rangefinders, from expensive Leicas to "point-and-shoot" pocket cameras, were all using 35 mm film, and manufacturers had proliferated.
[src:cobol/135-film] Colour films improved, both for print negatives and reversal slides, while black-and-white films offered smoother grain and faster speeds than previously available.
[src:cobol/135-film] Since 35 mm was preferred by both amateur and professional photographers, makers of film stock have long offered the widest range of different film speeds and types in the format.
[src:cobol/135-film] The DX film-speed encoding system was introduced in the 1980s, as were single-use cameras pre-loaded with 35 mm film and using plastic lenses of reasonable enough quality to produce acceptable snapshots.
[src:cobol/135-film] Automated all-in-one processing and printing machines made 35 mm developing easier and less expensive, so that quality colour prints became available not only from photographic specialty stores, but also from supermarkets, drugstores, and big box retailers, often in less than an hour.
[src:cobol/135-film] In 1996, a smaller format called Advanced Photo System (APS) was introduced by a consortium of photographic companies in an attempt to supersede 135 film.
[src:cobol/135-film] Due in part to its small negative size, APS was not taken seriously as a professional format, despite the production of APS SLRs.
[src:cobol/135-film] In the point-and-shoot markets at which the format was primarily aimed, it enjoyed moderate initial success, but still never rivalled the market penetration of 135.
[src:cobol/135-film] Within five years of its launch, cheap digital compact cameras started becoming widely available, and APS sales plummeted.
[src:cobol/135-film] Introductory 35 mm SLRs, compact film point-and-shoot cameras, and single-use cameras continue to be built and sold by a number of makers.
[src:cobol/135-film] Leica introduced the digital Leica M8 rangefinder in 2007, but continues to make its M series rangefinder film cameras and lenses.
[src:cobol/135-film] A digital camera back for the Leica R9 SLR camera was discontinued in 2007.
[src:cobol/135-film] On March 25, 2009, Leica discontinued the R9 SLR and R-series lenses.
[src:cobol/135-film] By the early 2020s, film photography, particularly 35 mm photography, was experiencing a resurgence in popularity.
[src:cobol/135-film] In a 2021 PetaPixel survey, 75% of respondents expressed interest in newly manufactured analog cameras.
[src:cobol/135-film] Kodak reported in 2022 that it was having trouble keeping up with demand for 35 mm film.
[src:cobol/135-film] In 2024, the Pentax 17 and the Aflie TYCH+ 35 mm cameras were released, both using the half-frame format to conserve film.
[src:cobol/135-film] Retrospekt and Mattel put out the Malibu Barbie FC-11 35 mm camera.
[src:cobol/135-film] In September 2024, MiNT Camera took pre-orders for the Rollei 35AF, an update of the Rollei 35.
[src:cobol/135-film] Kodak offered six 35 mm film cameras for sale as of October 2024, including the Ektar H35N, another half-frame camera.
[src:cobol/135-film] Individual rolls of 135 film are enclosed in single-spool, light-tight, metal cassettes, also known as film canisters, to allow cameras to be loaded in daylight.
[src:cobol/135-film] The film is clipped or taped to a spool and exits via a slot lined with flocking.
[src:cobol/135-film] The end of the film is cut on one side to form a leader.
[src:cobol/135-film] It has the same dimensions and perforation pitch as 35 mm movie print film (also called "long pitch", KS-1870, whereas 35 mm professional motion picture camera films are always "short pitch", BH-1866).
[src:cobol/135-film] Most cameras require the film to be rewound before the camera is opened.
[src:cobol/135-film] Some motorized cameras unwind the film fully upon loading and then expose the images in reverse order, returning the film to the cassette; this protects all exposed frames (except the last one or two), should the camera back be accidentally opened; unexposed film gets spoiled, however.
[src:cobol/135-film] Disposable cameras use the same technique so that the user does not have to rewind.
[src:cobol/135-film] Since 1983, most film cassettes have been marked with a DX encoding six-digit barcode pattern, which uses a DX number to identify the manufacturer and film type (and thus processing method), and the number of exposures, for the use of photofinishing laboratories.
[src:cobol/135-film] Conforming cameras detect at least some of these areas; only three contacts are needed to set a light meter for the four most popular film speeds.
[src:cobol/135-film] The 135 film has been made in several emulsion types and sensitivities (film speeds) described by ISO standards.
[src:cobol/135-film] Since the introduction of digital cameras the most usual films have colour emulsions of ISO 100/21° to ISO 800/30°.
[src:cobol/135-film] Films of lower sensitivity (and better picture quality) and higher sensitivity (for low light) are for more specialist purposes.
[src:cobol/135-film] There are colour and monochrome films, negative and positive.
[src:cobol/135-film] Monochrome film is usually panchromatic; orthochromatic has fallen out of use.
[src:cobol/135-film] Film designed to be sensitive to infrared radiation can be obtained, both monochrome and with false-colour (or pseudocolour) rendition.
[src:cobol/135-film] More exotic emulsions have been available in 135 than other roll-film sizes.
[src:cobol/135-film] The term *135 format* usually refers to a 24×36 mm film format, commonly known as 35 mm format.
[src:cobol/135-film] The 24×36 mm format is common to higher-end digital image sensors, where it is typically referred to as *full-frame* format.
[src:cobol/135-film] On 135 film, the typical cameras produce a frame where the longer dimension of the 24×36 mm frame runs parallel to the length of the film.
[src:cobol/135-film] The perforation size and pitch are according to the standard specification KS-1870.
[src:cobol/135-film] For each frame, the film advances 8 perforations.
[src:cobol/135-film] This allows for 2 mm gaps between frames.
[src:cobol/135-film] Camera models typically have different locations for the sprocket which advances the film.
[src:cobol/135-film] Therefore, each camera model's frame may vary in position relative to the perforations.
[src:cobol/135-film] The film is approximately 0.14 mm thick.
[src:cobol/135-film] Other image formats have been applied to 135 film, such as the half-frame format of 18×24 mm which earned some popularity in the 1960s, and the 24×24 mm of the Robot cameras.
[src:cobol/135-film] The successful range of Olympus Pen F cameras utilized the smaller half-frame size, allowing the design of a very compact SLR camera.
[src:cobol/135-film] Unusual formats include the 24×32 mm and 24×34 mm on the early Nikon rangefinders, and 24×23 mm for use with some stereo cameras.
[src:cobol/135-film] In 1967, the Soviet KMZ factory introduced a 24×58 mm panoramic format with its Horizont camera (descendants of which are called, in the Roman alphabet, Horizon).
[src:cobol/135-film] In 1998, Hasselblad and Fuji introduced a 24×65 mm panoramic format with their XPan/TX-1 camera.
[src:cobol/135-film] There is also a 21×14 mm format used by Tessina subminiature camera.
[src:cobol/135-film] The film is available in lengths for varying numbers of exposures.
[src:cobol/135-film] The standard full-length roll has always been 36 exposures (assuming a standard 24×36 frame size).
[src:cobol/135-film] Through about 1980, 20 exposure rolls were the only shorter length with widespread availability.
[src:cobol/135-film] Since then, 20 exposure rolls have been largely discontinued in favour of 24- and 12-exposure rolls.
[src:cobol/135-film] A camera that uses less than the maximum distance between the spools may be able to make one additional exposure.
[src:cobol/135-film] Self-loading cameras that load the film after being closed don't spoil the additional length provided for conventional loading and can make that additional length available for two or three additional exposures.
[src:cobol/135-film] The same length can be available for exposure in any camera if it is loaded without exposing the film to light, e.g. in a dark room or a dark bag.
[src:cobol/135-film] A 27-exposure disposable camera uses a standard 24-exposure cassette loaded in the dark.
[src:cobol/135-film] Other, mostly shorter, lengths have been manufactured.
[src:cobol/135-film] There have been some 6-, 8-, 10-, and 15-exposure rolls given away as samples, sometimes in disposable cameras, or used by insurance adjusters to document damage claims.
[src:cobol/135-film] Twelve-exposure rolls have been used widely in the daily press.
[src:cobol/135-film] Photographers who load their own cassettes can use any length of film – with a thinner film base, up to 45 exposures will fit.
[src:cobol/135-film] The Ilford HP black-and-white film, on a thin polyester base, allowed 72 exposures in a single cassette.
[src:cobol/135-film] They produced special reels and tanks to allow this to be processed.
[src:cobol/135-film] Digital sensors are available in various sizes.
[src:cobol/135-film] Professional DSLR cameras usually use digital image sensors which approximate the dimensions of the 35 mm format, sometimes differing by fractions of a millimetre on one or both dimensions.
[src:cobol/135-film] Since 2007, Nikon has referred to their 35 mm format by the trade mark FX.
[src:cobol/135-film] Other makers of 35 mm format digital cameras, including Leica, Sony, and Canon, refer to their 35 mm sensors simply as full frame.
[src:cobol/135-film] Most consumer DSLR cameras use smaller sensors, with the most popular size being APS-C which measures around 23×15 mm (giving it a crop factor of 1.5–1.6).
[src:cobol/135-film] Compact cameras have smaller sensors with a crop factor of around 3 to 6.
[src:cobol/135-film] Most smartphones (as of 2024) have a default aspect ratio of 4:3 (1.33).
[src:cobol/135-film] Mimicking 35mm film in a smartphone requires cropping to a 3:2 (1.5) aspect ratio.
[src:cobol/135-film] For an authentic homage, one can apply creative digital filters like the ones commonly used in Instagram that map the colour profile to a characteristic look.
[src:cobol/135-film] Different brands of 35mm film would achieve the creative colour profile through a chemical process.
[src:cobol/135-film] For example Fuji Velvia film gave the photo a characteristic of saturated colours under daylight, high contrast, and exceptional sharpness.
[src:cobol/135-film] A true normal lens for 35 mm format would have a focal length of 43 mm, the diagonal measurement of the format.
[src:cobol/135-film] However, lenses of 43 mm to 60 mm are commonly considered *normal* lenses for the format, in mass production and popular use.
[src:cobol/135-film] Common focal lengths of lenses made for the format include 24, 28, 35, 50, 85, 105, and 135 mm.
[src:cobol/135-film] Most commonly, a 50 mm lens is the one considered *normal*; any lens shorter than this is considered a *wide angle* lens and anything above is considered a *telephoto* lens.
[src:cobol/135-film] Even then, wide angles shorter than 24 mm is called an *extreme wide angle*.
[src:cobol/135-film] Lenses above 50 mm but up to about 100 mm are called short telephoto or sometimes, as *portrait telephotos*, from 100 mm to about 200 mm are called *medium* telephotos, and above 300 mm are called *long* telephotos.
[src:cobol/135-film] With many smaller formats now common (such as APS-C), lenses are often advertised or marked with their "35 mm equivalent" or "full-frame equivalent" focal length as a mnemonic, due to the historic prevalence of the 35 mm format.
[src:cobol/135-film] This 'equivalent' is computed by multiplying (a) the true focal length of the lens by (b) the ratio of the diagonal measurement of the native format to that of the 35 mm format.
[src:cobol/135-film] As a result, a lens for an APS-C (18×24 mm) format camera body with a focal length of 40 mm, might be described as "60 mm (35 mm equivalent)".
[src:cobol/135-film] Although its true focal length remains 40 mm, its angle of view is equivalent to that of a 60 mm lens on a 35 mm format (24×36 mm) camera.
[src:cobol/135-film] Another example is the lens of the 2/3 inch format Fujifilm X10, which is marked with its true zoom range "7.1–28.4 mm" but has a 35 mm-equivalent zoom range of "28–112 mm".
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A **19-inch rack** is a standardized frame or enclosure for mounting multiple electronic equipment modules.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Each module has a front panel that is 19 inches (482.6 mm) wide.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The 19 inch dimension includes the edges or *ears* that protrude from each side of the equipment, allowing the module to be fastened to the rack frame with screws or bolts.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Common uses include computer servers, telecommunications equipment and networking hardware, audiovisual production gear, professional audio equipment, and scientific equipment.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Equipment designed to be placed in a rack is typically described as **rack-mount**/**rack-mountable**, a **rack-mount instrument**, **rack-mounted system**, or **rack-mount chassis**.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The rack may include subracks or shelves.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The height of the mountable equipment is standardized as multiples of 1.75 inches (44.45 mm) or one *rack unit* or *U* (less commonly *RU*).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The industry-standard rack cabinet is 42U tall; however, many data centers have racks taller than this.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The term **relay rack** appeared first in the late 19th century, in the world of telephony.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] By 1911, the term was also being used in railroad signaling.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] There is little evidence that the dimensions of these early racks were standardized.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch rack format with rack units of 1.75 inches (44.45 mm) was established as a standard by AT&T around 1922 in order to reduce the space required for repeater and termination equipment in a telephone company central office.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The earliest repeaters from 1914 were installed in ad hoc fashion on shelves, in wooden boxes and cabinets.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Once serial production started, they were built into custom-made racks, one per repeater.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] But in light of the rapid growth of the toll network, the engineering department of AT&T undertook a systematic redesign, resulting in a family of modular factory-assembled panels all "designed to mount on vertical supports spaced 191⁄2 inches between centers.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] By 1934, it was an established standard with holes tapped for 12-24 screws with alternating spacings of 1.25 inches (31.75 mm) and 0.5 inches (12.70 mm).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch rack format has remained constant while the technology that is mounted within it has changed considerably and the set of fields to which racks are applied has greatly expanded.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch (482.6 mm) standard rack arrangement is widely used throughout the telecommunications, computing, audio, video, entertainment and other industries, though the Western Electric 23-inch standard, with holes on 1-inch (25.4 mm) centers, is still used in legacy ILEC/CLEC facilities.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Nineteen-inch racks in two-post or four-post form hold most equipment in enterprise data centers, Internet service provider facilities, and professionally designed corporate server rooms, although hyperscale computing typically use wider racks.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] They allow for dense hardware configurations without occupying excessive floor space or requiring shelving.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Nineteen-inch racks are also often used to house professional audio and video equipment, including amplifiers, effects units, interfaces, headphone amplifiers, and even small-scale audio mixers.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A third common use for rack-mounted equipment is industrial power, control, and automation hardware.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Typically, a piece of equipment being installed has a front panel height 1⁄32 inch (0.031 in; 0.79 mm) less than the allotted number of Us.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Thus, a 1U rackmount computer is not 1.750 inches (44.5 mm) tall but is 1.719 inches (43.7 mm) tall.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] If *n* is the number of rack units, the ideal formula for panel height is *h* = 1.75*n* − 0.031 for calculating in inches, and *h* = 44.45*n* − 0.794 for calculating in millimeters.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] This gap allows a bit of room above and below an installed piece of equipment so it may be removed without binding on the adjacent equipment.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Originally, the mounting holes were tapped with a particular screw thread.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] When rack rails are too thin to tap, rivet nuts or other threaded inserts can be used, and when the particular class of equipment to be mounted is known in advance, some of the holes can be omitted from the mounting rails.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Threaded mounting holes in racks where the equipment is frequently changed are problematic because the threads can be damaged or the mounting screws can break off; both problems render the mounting hole unusable.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Tapping large numbers of holes that may never be used is expensive; nonetheless, tapped-hole racks are still in use, generally for hardware that rarely changes.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Examples include telephone exchanges, network cabling panels, broadcast studios and some government and military applications.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The tapped-hole rack was first replaced by clearance-hole (Round Hole, Round Unthreaded Holes, and Versa Rail) racks.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The holes are large enough to permit a bolt to be freely inserted through without binding, and bolts are fastened in place using cage nuts.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] In the event of a nut being stripped out or a bolt breaking, the nut can be easily removed and replaced with a new one.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Production of clearance-hole racks is less expensive.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The next innovation in rack design has been the square-hole rack.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Square-hole racks allow boltless mounting, such that the rack-mount equipment only needs to insert through and hook down into the lip of the square hole.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Installation and removal of hardware in a square-hole rack is very easy and boltless, where the weight of the equipment and small retention clips are all that is necessary to hold the equipment in place.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Older equipment meant for round-hole or tapped-hole racks can still be used, with the use of cage nuts made for square-hole racks.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable equipment is traditionally mounted by bolting or clipping its front panel to the rack.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Within the IT industry, it is common for network/communications equipment to have multiple mounting positions, including tabletop and wall mounting, so rack-mountable equipment will often feature L-brackets that must be screwed or bolted to the equipment prior to mounting in a 19-inch rack.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] With the prevalence of 23-inch racks in the Telecoms industry, the same practice is also common, but with equipment having 19-inch and 23-inch brackets available, enabling them to be mounted in existing racks.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A key structural weakness of front-mounted support is the bending stress placed on the mounting brackets of the equipment and the rack itself.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] As a result, 4-post racks have become common, featuring a mirrored pair of rear mounting posts.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Servers and deep pieces of equipment are often mounted using rails that are bolted to the front and rear posts (as above, it is common for such rails to have an adjustable depth), allowing the equipment to be supported by four posts, while also enabling it to be easily installed and removed.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] This, of course, varies by manufacturer, the design of the rack and its purpose, but through common constraining factors (such as raised-floor tile dimensions), these dimensions have become quite common.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The extra width and depth enable cabling to be routed with ease (also helping to maintain the minimum bend radius for fiber and copper cables) and deeper equipment to be utilized.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A common feature in IT racks is mounting positions for *zero-U* accessories, such as power distribution units (PDUs) and vertical cable managers and ducts, that utilize the space between the rear rails and the side of the rack enclosure.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The strength required of the mounting posts means they are invariably not merely flat strips but actually a wider folded strip arranged around the corner of the rack.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The posts are usually made of steel of around 2 mm thickness (the official standard recommends a minimum of 1.9 mm), or of slightly thicker aluminum.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Racks, especially two-post racks, are often secured to the floor or adjacent building structure so as not to fall over.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] This is usually required by local building codes in seismic zones.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] According to Telcordia Technologies Generic Requirements document GR-63-CORE, during an earthquake, telecommunications equipment is subjected to motions that can over-stress the equipment framework, circuit boards, and connectors.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The amount of motion and resulting stress depends on the structural characteristics of the building and framework in which the equipment is contained and the severity of the earthquake.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Seismic racks rated according to GR-63, *NEBS Requirements: Physical Protection,* are available, with Zone 4 representing the most demanding environment.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] GR-3108, *Generic Requirements for Network Equipment in the Outside Plant (OSP),* specifies the usable opening of seismic-compliant 19-inch racks.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Heavy equipment or equipment that is commonly accessed for servicing, for which attaching or detaching at all four corners simultaneously would pose a problem, is often not mounted directly onto the rack but instead is mounted via rails (or slides).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A pair of rails is mounted directly onto the rack, and the equipment then slides into the rack along the rails, which support it.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] When in place, the equipment may also then be bolted to the rack.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The rails may also be able to fully support the equipment in a position where it has been slid clear of the rack; this is useful for inspection or maintenance of equipment, which will then be slid back into the rack.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Some rack slides even include a tilt mechanism allowing easy access to the top or bottom of rack-mounted equipment when it is fully extended from the rack.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A rails kit may include a cable management arm (CMA), which folds the cables attached to the server and allows them to expand neatly when the server is slid out, without being disconnected.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] When there is a large number of computers in a single rack, it is impractical for each one to have its own separate keyboard, mouse, and monitor.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Instead, a KVM switch or LOM software is used to share a single keyboard/video/mouse set amongst many different computers.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Since the mounting hole arrangement is vertically symmetric, it is possible to mount rack-mountable equipment upside-down.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] However, not all equipment is suitable for this type of mounting.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] For instance, most optical disc players will not work upside-down because the driving motor mechanism does not grip the disc.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A standard 19-inch server rack cabinet is typically 42u in height, 600 millimetres (24 in) wide, and 36 inches (914.40 mm) deep.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] This comprises a volume of 974 L, or just under a cubic meter.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Newer server rack cabinets come with adjustable mounting rails, allowing the user to place the rails at a shorter depth if needed.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] There are a multitude of specialty server racks, including soundproof server racks, air-conditioned server racks, NEMA-rated, seismic-rated, open frame, narrow, and even miniature 19-inch racks for smaller applications.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Cabinets are generally sized to be no wider than the standard 24-inch-wide (610 mm) floor tiles used in most data centers.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Racks carrying telecom equipment like routers and switches often have extra width to accommodate the many cables on the sides.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] 19-inch equipment that needs to be moved often or protected from harsh treatment can be housed in a *road case* approved by the Air Transport Association of America (ATA), sometimes also referred to as a *flight case*.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Road cases typically have plywood sides laminated with polyvinyl chloride (PVC), extruded aluminum edges, steel corners, handles, and latches.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Larger cases typically have wheels for easy transport.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Road case racks come in different heights based on the 1U standard and different depths.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Non-isolated cases simply mount 19-inch mounting posts inside the case.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] To protect equipment from shock and vibration, road rack cases use an inner and outer case.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] These cases can be isolated by thick layers of foam or may use spring-loaded shock mounting.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Touring musicians, theatrical productions and sound and light companies use road case racks.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Rack strips used for road cases come in 2 types: single angle and double angle.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Double-angle rack strips offer better structural strength and an additional mounting face for cable management or additional support for heavy equipment.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] In 1965, a durable fiber-reinforced plastic 19-inch rackmount case was patented by ECS Composites and became widely used in military and commercial applications for electronic deployment and operation.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Rackmount cases are also constructed of thermo-stamped composite, carbon fiber, and DuPont's Kevlar for military and commercial uses.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Portable rack cases using a rotary-molded polyethylene outer shell are a lower-cost alternative to the more durable ATA-approved case.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] These cases are marketed to musicians and entertainers for equipment not subject to frequent transportation and rough handling.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The polyethylene shell is not fiberglass reinforced and is not rigid.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The shape of small cases is maintained by the rack rails and the cover seal extrusions alone.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Larger cases are further reinforced with additional plywood or sheet metal.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The outer shell is frequently embossed in a self-mating pattern to combat the tendency for stacked cases to deform slightly, creating a slope that encourages the upper case to slide off.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The cases typically use extruded aluminum bands at the ends of the body with tongue-and-groove mating to like bands for the covers.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] End covers are typically secured with either a simple draw latch or a rotary cam *butterfly* latch, named for the shape of the twist handle.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] There is no standard for airflow and cooling of rack-mounted equipment.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A variety of airflow patterns can be found, including front intakes and rear exhausts, as well as side intakes and exhausts.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Low-wattage devices may not employ active cooling, but use only passive thermal radiation and convection to dissipate heat.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] For rack-mounted computer servers, devices generally intake air on the front and exhaust on the rear.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] This prevents circular airflows where hot exhaust air is recirculated through an adjacent device and causes overheating.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Although open-frame racks are the least expensive, they also expose air-cooled equipment to dust, lint, and other environmental contamination.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] An enclosed sealed cabinet with forced air fans permits air filtration to protect equipment from dust.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Large server rooms will often group rack cabinets together so that racks on both sides of an aisle are either front-facing or rear-facing, which simplifies cooling by supplying cool air to the front of the racks and collecting hot air from the rear of the racks.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] These aisles may themselves be enclosed in a cold air containment tunnel so that cooling air does not travel to other parts of the building where it is not needed or mixes with hot air, making it less efficient.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Raised or false floor cooling in server rooms can serve a similar purpose; they permit cooling airflow to equipment through the underfloor space to the underside of enclosed rack cabinets.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A difficulty with forced air fan cooling in rack equipment is that fans can fail due to age or dust.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The fans themselves can be difficult to replace.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] In the case of network equipment, it may be necessary to unplug 50 or more cables from the device, remove the device from the rack, and then disassemble the device chassis to replace the fans.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] However, some rack equipment has been designed to make fan replacement easy, using quick-change fan trays that can be accessed without removing the cabling or the device from the rack, and in some cases without turning off the device so that operation is uninterrupted during replacement.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A rack's mounting fixture consists of two parallel metal strips (also referred to as *posts* or *panel mounts*) standing vertically.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The posts are each 0.625 inches (15.88 mm) wide, and are separated by a gap of 17.75 inches (450.85 mm), giving an overall rack width of 19 inches (482.60 mm).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The posts have holes in them at regular intervals, with both posts matching, so that each hole is part of a horizontal pair with a center-to-center distance of 18.28–18.34 inches (464.2–465.8 mm).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The holes in the posts are arranged vertically in repeating sets of three, with center-to-center separations of 0.5, 0.625, 0.625 inches (12.70, 15.88, 15.88 mm).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The hole pattern thus repeats every 1.75 inches (44.45 mm).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Holes so arranged can either be tapped (usually 10-32 UNF thread, or, less often, 6mm metric) or have square holes for cage nuts.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Racks are vertically divided into regions, 44.45 millimetres (1.75 in) in height.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Each region has three complete hole pairs on each side.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The holes are centered at 6.35 millimetres (0.25 in), 22.25 millimetres (0.88 in), and 38.1 millimetres (1.50 in) from the top or bottom of the region.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Such a region is commonly known as a **U**, for *unit*, **RU** for *rack unit* or, in German, **HE**, for *Höheneinheit*.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Heights within racks are measured by this unit.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable equipment is usually designed to occupy some integer number of U.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] For example, an oscilloscope might be 4U high.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable computers and servers are mostly between 1U and 4U high.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A blade server enclosure might require 10U.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Occasionally, one may see fractional U devices, such as a 1.5U server or devices that are just 22.5 or 15 cm in width, allowing for 2 or 3 such devices to be installed side by side, but these are much less common.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The height of a rack can vary from a few inches, such as in a broadcast console, to a floor-mounted rack whose interior is 45 rack units (200.2 centimetres or 78.82 inches) high.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Many wall-mounted enclosures for industrial equipment use 19-inch racks.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Some telecommunications and networking equipment is available in a narrower 10-inch format with the same unit height as a standard 19-inch rack.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] This standard is also gaining in popularity with hobbyists with limited space at their disposal.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Frames for holding rotary-dial telephone equipment, such as step-by-step telephone switches, were generally 11 feet 6 inches (3.51 m) high.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A series of studies led to the adoption of frames 7 feet (2.1 m) high, with modular widths in multiples of 1 foot 1 inch (0.33 m)—most often 2 feet 2 inches (0.66 m) wide.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The **ETSI rack** is defined by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETS 300 119).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The distance of the right edge of the right mounting rail to the left edge of the left mounting rail is 535 millimetres (21.1 in).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] As 535 mm is very close to 21 inches, these racks are sometimes called *21-inch racks*.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The gap between the posts is 500 millimetres (19.69 in).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] As 19-inch equipment has a maximum width of 17+1⁄4 inches (438.15 mm), they can easily be mounted in an ETSI rack by means of an ETSI bracket or adapter plate.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] In contrast to the 19-inch standards, ETSI also defined the size of the rack enclosure: the four allowed widths are 150, 300, 600, 900 millimetres (5.9, 11.8, 23.6, 35.4 in) and two allowed depths are 300 and 600 millimetres (12 and 24 in).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Hole spacing is 25 millimetres (0.98 in).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] A 23-inch (580 mm) rack is used for housing telephone (primarily), computer, audio and other equipment – although it is less common than the 19-inch rack.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The size denotes the width of the faceplate for the installed equipment.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The rack unit is a measure of vertical spacing and is common to both the 19 and 23-inch racks.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Hole spacing is either on 1-inch (25 mm) centers (Western Electric standard), or the same as for 19-inch (482.6 mm) racks (0.625 in or 15.9 mm spacing).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Open Rack is a mounting system designed by the Open Compute Project that has the same outside dimensions as typical 19-inch racks (e.g., 600 mm width), but internally supports wider equipment modules of 547 millimetres (21.5 in).
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] OpenVPX is an industry standard for modules that can be installed in a chassis in defense applications.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The modules can provide a variety of functions, similar to equipment in a rack.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Eurorack is a standard generally used in electronic music production to install components of a modular synthesizer, an electronic music instrument.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] This is achieved with a rack mounting system specific to the standard.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Eurocard is an IEEE standard format for printed circuit board (PCB) cards that can be plugged together into a standard chassis, which, in turn, can be mounted in a 19-inch rack.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] The chassis consists of a series of slotted card guides on the top and bottom, into which the cards are slid so they stand on end, like books on a shelf.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] At the spine of each card is one or more connectors which plug into mating connectors on a backplane that closes the rear of the chassis.
[src:cobol/19-inch-rack] Several standards such as VMEbus (Versa Module Eurocard bus), STEbus, PCI eXtensions for Instrumentation, openGear and others were developed, which share goals with Eurocard.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] Before standardization to 440 Hz, many countries and organizations followed the French standard since the 1860s of 435 Hz, which had also been the Austrian government's 1885 recommendation.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] Johann Heinrich Scheibler recommended A440 as a standard in 1834 after inventing the "tonometer" to measure pitch, and it was approved by the Society of German Natural Scientists and Physicians at a meeting in Stuttgart the same year.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] The American music industry reached an informal standard of 440 Hz in 1926, and some began using it in instrument manufacturing.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] In 1936, the American Standards Association recommended that the A above middle C be tuned to 440 Hz.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] In 1937 Sir James Swinburne, an electrical engineer and avid amateur musician, delivered a lecture to the Royal Musical Association on "The Ideal Scale," discussing the possibility of tuning a scale to pure ratios and adjusting these ratios to maintain consonance across different keys.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] The following year, Swinburne represented the Musical Association at a preliminary conference to determine the British stance on concert pitch.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] British piano tuners had adopted A439 as the standard in 1899, but Swinburne pointed out that 439 was a prime number, whereas 440 could be more easily factored and electronically synthesized.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] In May of 1939, delegates from France, Germany, The Netherlands, Italy, and England convened at Broadcasting House in London, the headquarters of the BBC, to address the issue of concert pitch.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] Representatives from Switzerland and the United States participated via mail.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] The other European delegates concurred with Swinburne's position and agreed to a standard of A440.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] This standard was taken up by the International Organization for Standardization in 1955 as Recommendation R 16, before being formalised in 1975 as **ISO 16**.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] The A440 standard is not universally adhered to.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] Early-music ensembles continue to use older, lower pitch levels.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] Leonard Bernstein often tuned the New York Philharmonic to A442, leading to complaints from the piano tuners' union, although he claimed both the New York and Boston orchestras had used this higher pitch for years.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] A440 is widely used as concert pitch in the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] In continental Europe the frequency of A4 commonly varies between 440 Hz and 444 Hz.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] A440 is often used as a tuning reference in just intonation regardless of the fundamental note or key.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] The US time and frequency station WWV broadcasts a 440 Hz signal at two minutes past every hour, with WWVH broadcasting the same tone at the first minute past every hour.
[src:cobol/a440-pitch-standard] This was added in 1936 to aid orchestras in tuning their instruments.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] COBOL's design was started in 1959 by CODASYL and was partly based on the programming language FLOW-MATIC, designed by Grace Hopper.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] It was created as part of a US Department of Defense effort to create a portable programming language for data processing.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] It was originally seen as a stopgap, but the Defense Department promptly pressured computer manufacturers to provide it, resulting in its widespread adoption.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] It was standardized in 1968 and has been revised five times.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Expansions include support for structured and object-oriented programming.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The current standard is ISO/IEC 1989:2023.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] COBOL statements have prose syntax such as `MOVE x TO y`, which was designed to be self-documenting and highly readable.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] However, it is verbose and uses over 300 reserved words compared to the succinct and mathematically inspired syntax of other languages.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The COBOL code is split into four *divisions* (identification, environment, data, and procedure), containing a rigid hierarchy of sections, paragraphs, and sentences.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Lacking a large standard library, the standard specifies 43 statements, 87 functions, and just one class.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] COBOL has been criticized for its verbosity, design process, and poor support for structured programming.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] These weaknesses often result in monolithic programs that are hard to comprehend as a whole, despite their local readability.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] For years, COBOL has been assumed as a programming language for business operations in mainframes, although in recent years, many COBOL operations have been moved to cloud computing.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In the late 1950s, computer users and manufacturers were becoming concerned about the rising cost of programming.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] A 1959 survey had found that in any data processing installation, the programming cost US$800,000 on average and that translating programs to run on new hardware would cost US$600,000.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] At a time when new programming languages were proliferating, the same survey suggested that if a common business-oriented language were used, conversion would be far cheaper and faster.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Hawes, a computer scientist at Burroughs Corporation, called a meeting of representatives from academia, computer users, and manufacturers at the University of Pennsylvania to organize a formal meeting on common business languages.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Representatives included Grace Hopper (inventor of the English-like data processing language FLOW-MATIC), Jean Sammet, and Saul Gorn.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] At the April meeting, the group asked the Department of Defense (DoD) to sponsor an effort to create a common business language.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Phillips, director of the Data System Research Staff at the DoD, who thought that they "thoroughly understood" the DoD's problems.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The DoD operated 225 computers, had 175 more on order, and had spent over $200 million on implementing programs to run on them.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Portable programs would save time, reduce costs, and ease modernization.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Charles Phillips agreed to sponsor the meeting, and tasked the delegation with drafting the agenda.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] On 28 and 29 May 1959, a meeting was held at the Pentagon to discuss the creation of a common programming language for business (exactly one year after the Zürich ALGOL 58 meeting).
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] It was attended by 41 people and was chaired by Phillips.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The Department of Defense was concerned about whether it could run the same data processing programs on different computers.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] FORTRAN, the only mainstream language at the time, lacked the features needed to write such programs.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Representatives enthusiastically described a language that could work in a wide variety of environments, from banking and insurance to utilities and inventory control.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] They agreed unanimously that more people should be able to program, and that the new language should not be restricted by the limitations of contemporary technology.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] A majority agreed that the language should make maximal use of English, be capable of change, be machine-independent, and be easy to use, even at the expense of power.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The meeting resulted in the creation of a steering committee and short, intermediate, and long-range committees.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The short-range committee was given until September (three months) to produce specifications for an interim language, which would then be improved upon by the other committees.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Their official mission, however, was to identify the strengths and weaknesses of existing programming languages; it did not explicitly direct them to create a new language.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The deadline was met with disbelief by the short-range committee.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] One member, Betty Holberton, described the three-month deadline as "gross optimism" and doubted that the language really would be a stopgap.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The steering committee met on 4 June and agreed to name the entire activity the *Committee on Data Systems Languages*, or CODASYL, and to form an executive committee.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The short-range committee members represented six computer manufacturers and three government agencies.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The computer manufacturers were Burroughs Corporation, IBM, Minneapolis-Honeywell (Honeywell Labs), RCA, Sperry Rand, and Sylvania Electric Products.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Air Force, the Navy's David Taylor Model Basin, and the National Bureau of Standards (now the National Institute of Standards and Technology).
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The committee was chaired by Joseph Wegstein of the U.S.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Work began by investigating data descriptions, statements, existing applications, and user experiences.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The committee mainly examined the FLOW-MATIC, AIMACO, and COMTRAN programming languages.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The FLOW-MATIC language was particularly influential because it had been implemented and because AIMACO was a derivative of it with only minor changes.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] FLOW-MATIC's inventor, Grace Hopper, also served as a technical adviser to the committee.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] FLOW-MATIC's major contributions to COBOL were long variable names, English words for commands, and the separation of data descriptions and instructions.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] IBM's COMTRAN language, invented by Bob Bemer, was regarded as a competitor to FLOW-MATIC by a short-range committee made up of colleagues of Grace Hopper.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Some of its features were not incorporated into COBOL so that it would not look like IBM had dominated the design process, and Jean Sammet said in 1981 that there had been a "strong anti-IBM bias" from some committee members (herself included).
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In 1980, Grace Hopper commented that "COBOL 60 is 95% FLOW-MATIC" and that COMTRAN had had an "extremely small" influence.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Furthermore, she said that she would claim that work was influenced by both FLOW-MATIC and COMTRAN only to "keep other people happy [so they] wouldn't try to knock us out.".
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Features from COMTRAN incorporated into COBOL included formulas, the `PICTURE` clause, an improved `IF` statement which obviated the need for GO TOs, and a more robust file management system.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The usefulness of the committee's work was a subject of great debate.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] While some members thought the language had too many compromises and was the result of design by committee, others felt it was better than the three languages examined.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Some felt the language was too complex; others, too simple.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Controversial features included those some considered useless or too advanced for data processing users.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Such features included Boolean expressions, formulas, and table **subscripts** (indices).
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Another point of controversy was whether to make keywords context-sensitive and the effect that would have on readability.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Although context-sensitive keywords were rejected, the approach was later used in PL/I and partially in COBOL from 2002.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Little consideration was given to interactivity, interaction with operating systems (few existed at that time), and functions (thought of as purely mathematical and of no use in data processing).
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The specifications were presented to the executive committee on 4 September.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] They fell short of expectations: Joseph Wegstein noted that "it contains rough spots and requires some additions," and Bob Bemer later described them as a "hodgepodge." The committee was given until December to improve it.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] At a mid-September meeting, the committee discussed the new language's name.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Suggestions included "BUSY" (Business System), "INFOSYL" (Information System Language), and "COCOSYL" (Common Computer Systems Language).
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] It is unclear who coined the name "COBOL", although Bob Bemer later claimed it had been his suggestion.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In October, the intermediate-range committee received copies of the FACT language specification created by Roy Nutt.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Its features impressed the committee so much that they passed a resolution to base COBOL on it.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] This was a blow to the short-range committee, who had made good progress on the specification.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Despite being technically superior, FACT had not been created with portability in mind or through manufacturer and user consensus.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] It also lacked a demonstrable implementation, allowing supporters of a FLOW-MATIC-based COBOL to overturn the resolution.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] RCA representative Howard Bromberg also blocked FACT, so that RCA's work on a COBOL implementation would not go to waste.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] It soon became apparent that the committee was too large to make any further progress quickly.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] A frustrated Howard Bromberg bought a $15 tombstone (in 1959; equivalent to $170 in 2025) with "COBOL" engraved on it and sent it to Charles Phillips to demonstrate his displeasure.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The subcommittee did most of the work creating the specification, leaving the short-range committee to review and modify their work before producing the finished specification.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The specifications were approved by the executive committee on 8 January 1960, and sent to the government printing office, which printed them as *COBOL 60*.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The language's stated objectives were to allow efficient, portable programs to be easily written, to allow users to move to new systems with minimal effort and cost, and to be suitable for inexperienced programmers.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The CODASYL Executive Committee later created the COBOL Maintenance Committee to answer questions from users and vendors and to improve and expand the specifications.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] During 1960, the list of manufacturers planning to build COBOL compilers grew.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] By September, five more manufacturers had joined CODASYL (Bendix, Control Data Corporation, General Electric (GE), National Cash Register, and Philco), and all represented manufacturers had announced COBOL compilers.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] GE and IBM planned to integrate COBOL into their own languages, GECOM and COMTRAN, respectively.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In contrast, International Computers and Tabulators planned to replace their language, CODEL, with COBOL.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Meanwhile, RCA and Sperry Rand worked on creating COBOL compilers.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The first COBOL program ran on 17 August on an RCA 501.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] On 6 and 7 December, the same COBOL program (albeit with minor changes) ran on an RCA computer and a Remington-Rand Univac computer, demonstrating that compatibility could be achieved.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Many logical flaws were found in *COBOL 60*, leading General Electric's Charles Katz to warn that it could not be interpreted unambiguously.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] A reluctant short-term committee performed a total cleanup, and, by March 1963, it was reported that COBOL's syntax was as definable as ALGOL's, although semantic ambiguities remained.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Early COBOL compilers were primitive and slow.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] A 1962 US Navy evaluation found compilation speeds of 3–11 statements per minute.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] By mid-1964, they had increased to 11–1000 statements per minute.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] It was observed that increasing memory would drastically increase speed and that compilation costs varied wildly: costs per statement were between $0.23 and $18.91.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In late 1962, IBM announced that COBOL would be their primary development language and that development of COMTRAN would cease.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The COBOL specification was revised three times in the five years after its publication.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] COBOL-60 was replaced in 1961 by COBOL-61.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] This was then replaced by the COBOL-61 Extended specifications in 1963, which introduced the sort and report writer facilities.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The added facilities corrected flaws identified by Honeywell in late 1959 in a letter to the short-range committee.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] COBOL Edition 1965 brought further clarifications to the specifications and introduced facilities for handling mass storage files and tables.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Efforts began to standardize COBOL to overcome incompatibilities between versions.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In late 1962, both ISO and the United States of America Standards Institute (now ANSI) formed groups to create standards.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] ANSI produced *USA Standard COBOL X3.23* in August 1968, which became the cornerstone for later versions.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] This version was known as American National Standard (ANS) COBOL and was adopted by ISO in 1972.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] By 1970, COBOL had become the most widely used programming language in the world.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Independently of the ANSI committee, the CODASYL Programming Language Committee was working on improving the language.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] They described new versions in 1968, 1969, 1970, and 1973, including changes such as new inter-program communication, debugging, and file merging facilities, as well as improved string handling and library inclusion features.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Although CODASYL was independent of the ANSI committee, the *CODASYL Journal of Development* was used by ANSI to identify features that were popular enough to warrant implementing.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The Programming Language Committee also liaised with ECMA and the Japanese COBOL Standard committee.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The Programming Language Committee was not well-known, however.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The vice president, William Rinehuls, complained that two-thirds of the COBOL community did not know of the committee's existence.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] It also lacked the funds to make public documents, such as minutes of meetings and change proposals, freely available.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In 1974, ANSI published a revised version of (ANS) COBOL, containing new features such as file organizations, the `DELETE` statement and the segmentation module.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Deleted features included the `NOTE` statement, the `EXAMINE` statement (which was replaced by `INSPECT`), and the implementer-defined random access module (which was superseded by the new sequential and relative I/O modules).
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] These made up 44 changes, which rendered existing statements incompatible with the new standard.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The report writer was slated to be removed from COBOL but was reinstated before the standard was published.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] ISO later adopted the updated standard in 1978.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In June 1978, work began on revising COBOL-74.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The proposed standard (commonly called COBOL-80) differed significantly from the previous one, causing concerns about incompatibility and conversion costs.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Brophy, Senior Vice-president of Travelers Insurance, threatened to sue the standard committee because it was not upwards compatible with COBOL-74.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Brophy described previous conversions of their 40-million-line code base as "non-productive" and a "complete waste of our programmer resources".
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Later that year, the Data Processing Management Association (DPMA) said it was "strongly opposed" to the new standard, citing "prohibitive" conversion costs and enhancements that were "forced on the user".
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] During the first public review period, the committee received 2,200 responses, of which 1,700 were negative form letters.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Other responses were detailed analyses of the effect COBOL-80 would have on their systems; conversion costs were predicted to be at least 50 cents per line of code.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Fewer than a dozen of the responses were in favor of the proposed standard.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] ISO TC97-SC5 installed in 1979 the international COBOL Experts Group, on initiative of Wim Ebbinkhuijsen.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The group consisted of COBOL experts from many countries, including the United States.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Its goal was to achieve mutual understanding and respect between ANSI and the rest of the world with regard to the need of new COBOL features.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] After three years, ISO changed the status of the group to a formal Working Group: WG 4 COBOL.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The group took primary ownership and development of the COBOL standard, where ANSI made most of the proposals.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In 1983, the DPMA withdrew its opposition to the standard, citing the responsiveness of the committee to public concerns.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In the same year, a National Bureau of Standards study concluded that the proposed standard would present few problems.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] A year later, DEC released a VAX/VMS COBOL-80, and noted that conversion of COBOL-74 programs posed few problems.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The new `EVALUATE` statement and inline `PERFORM` were particularly well received and improved productivity, thanks to simplified control flow and debugging.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The second public review drew another 1,000 (mainly negative) responses, while the last drew just 25, by which time many concerns had been addressed.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In 1985, the ISO Working Group 4 accepted the then-version of the ANSI proposed standard, made several changes and set it as the new ISO standard COBOL 85.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The new standard was adopted by all national standard bodies, including ANSI.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Two amendments followed in 1989, and 1993.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The first one introduced *Intrinsic function Module*, and the latter provided corrections.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In 1997, Gartner Group estimated that there were a total of 200 billion lines of COBOL in existence, which ran 80% of all business programs.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In the early 1990s, work began on adding object-oriented programming in the next full revision of COBOL.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Object-oriented features were taken from C++ and Smalltalk.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The initial estimate was to have this revision completed by 1997, and an ISO Committee Draft (CD) was available by 1997.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Some vendors (including Micro Focus, Fujitsu, and IBM) introduced object-oriented syntax based on drafts of the full revision.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The final approved ISO standard was approved and published in late 2002.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Fujitsu/GTSoftware, Micro Focus introduced object-oriented COBOL compilers targeting the .NET Framework.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] There were many other new features, many of which had been in the *CODASYL COBOL Journal of Development* since 1978 and had missed the opportunity to be included in COBOL-85.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Three corrigenda were published for the standard: two in 2006 and one in 2009.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Between 2003 and 2009, three Technical Reports (TRs) were produced describing object finalization, XML processing and collection classes for COBOL.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] COBOL 2002 suffered from poor support: no compilers completely supported the standard.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Micro Focus found that it was due to a lack of user demand for the new features and due to the abolition of the NIST test suite, which had been used to test compiler conformance.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The standardization process was also found to be slow and under-resourced.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] `gcobol`, from GCC 15.1, is based on this standard.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] COBOL programs are used globally in governments and various industries including retail, travel, finance, and healthcare.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] COBOL currently runs on diverse operating systems such as z/OS, z/VSE, VME, Unix, NonStop OS, OpenVMS and Windows.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In 1997, the Gartner Group reported that 80% of the world's business ran on COBOL with over 200 billion lines of code and 5 billion lines more being written annually.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] As of 2020, COBOL ran background processes 95% of the time a credit or debit card was swiped.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Near the end of the 20th century, the year 2000 problem (Y2K) was the focus of significant COBOL programming effort, sometimes by the same programmers who had designed the systems decades before.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The particular level of effort required to correct COBOL code has been attributed to the large amount of business-oriented COBOL, as business applications use dates heavily, and to fixed-length data fields.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Some studies attribute as much as "24% of Y2K software repair costs to Cobol".
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] After the clean-up effort put into these programs for Y2K, a 2003 survey found that many remained in use.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] The authors said that the survey data suggest "a gradual decline in the importance of COBOL in application development over the [following] 10 years unless ... integration with other languages and technologies can be adopted".
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In 2006 and 2012, *Computerworld* surveys (of 352 readers) found that over 60% of organizations used COBOL (more than C++ and Visual Basic .NET) and that for half of those, COBOL was used for the majority of their internal software.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] 36% of managers said they planned to migrate from COBOL, and 25% said that they would do so if not for the expense of rewriting legacy code.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Alternatively, some businesses have migrated their COBOL programs from mainframes to cheaper, faster hardware.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] By 2019, the number of COBOL programmers was shrinking fast due to retirements, leading to an impending skills gap in business and government organizations which still use mainframe systems for high-volume transaction processing.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Efforts to rewrite COBOL systems in newer languages have proven expensive and problematic, as has the outsourcing of code maintenance, thus proposals to train more people in COBOL are advocated.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Several banks have undertaken multi-year COBOL modernization efforts, sometimes resulting in widespread service disruptions that result in fines.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] During the COVID-19 pandemic and the ensuing surge of unemployment, several US states reported a shortage of skilled COBOL programmers to support the legacy systems used for unemployment benefit management.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Many of these systems had been in the process of conversion to more modern programming languages prior to the pandemic, but the process was put on hold.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] Similarly, the US Internal Revenue Service rushed to patch its COBOL-based Individual Master File in order to disburse the tens of millions of payments mandated by the Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act.
[src:cobol/cobol-p01] In 2024, the IRS announced a transition from COBOL to Java thanks to the Digital First Initiative.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] COBOL has an English-like syntax, which is used to describe nearly everything in COBOL programs.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] For example, a condition can be expressed as `x IS GREATER THAN y` or more concisely as `x GREATER y` or `x > y`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] More complex conditions can be abbreviated by removing repeated conditions and variables.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] For example, `a > b AND a > c OR a = d` can be shortened to `a > b AND c OR = d`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] To support this syntax, COBOL has over 300 keywords.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Some of the keywords are simple alternative or pluralized spellings of the same word, which provides for more grammatically appropriate statements and clauses; e.g., the `IN` and `OF` keywords can be used interchangeably, as can `TIME` and `TIMES`, and `VALUE` and `VALUES`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Each COBOL program is made up of four basic lexical items: words, literals, picture character-strings and separators.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Words include reserved words and user-defined identifiers.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] They are up to 31 characters long and may include letters, digits, hyphens and underscores.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Separators include the space character and commas and semi-colons followed by a space.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] A COBOL program is split into four divisions: the identification division, the environment division, the data division and the procedure division.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The identification division specifies the name and type of the source element and is where classes and interfaces are specified.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The environment division specifies any program features that depend on the system running it, such as files and character sets.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The data division is used to declare variables and parameters.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The procedure division contains the program's statements.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Each division is sub-divided into sections, which are made up of paragraphs.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] COBOL's syntax is usually described with a unique metalanguage using braces, brackets, bars and underlining.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The metalanguage was developed for the original COBOL specifications.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The height of COBOL's popularity coincided with the era of keypunch machines and punched cards.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The program itself was written onto punched cards, then read in and compiled, and the data fed into the program was sometimes on cards as well.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] COBOL can be written in two formats: fixed (the default) or free.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] In fixed-format, code must be aligned to fit in certain areas (a holdover from using punched cards).
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] In COBOL 2002, Areas A and B were merged to form the program-text area, which now ends at an implementor-defined column.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] COBOL 2002 also introduced free-format code.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Free-format code can be placed in any column of the file, as in newer programming languages.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Comments are specified using `*>`, which can be placed anywhere and can also be used in fixed-format source code.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Continuation lines are not present, and the `>>PAGE` directive replaces the `/` indicator.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The identification division identifies the following code entity and contains the definition of a class or interface.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Classes and interfaces have been in COBOL since 2002.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Classes have factory objects, containing class methods and variables, and instance objects, containing instance methods and variables.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Inheritance and interfaces provide polymorphism.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Support for generic programming is provided through parameterized classes, which can be instantiated to use any class or interface.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Objects are stored as references which may be restricted to a certain type.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] There are two ways of calling a method: the `INVOKE` statement, which acts similarly to `CALL`, or through inline method invocation, which is analogous to using functions.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] COBOL does not provide a way to hide methods.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Class data can be hidden, however, by declaring it without a `PROPERTY` clause, which leaves external code no way to access it.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Method overloading was added in COBOL 2014.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The environment division contains the configuration section and the input-output section.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The configuration section is used to specify variable features such as currency signs, locales and character sets.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The input-output section contains file-related information.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] COBOL supports three file formats, or **organizations**: sequential, indexed and relative.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] In sequential files, records are contiguous and must be traversed sequentially, similarly to a linked list.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Indexed files have one or more indexes which allow records to be randomly accessed and which can be sorted on them.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Each record must have a unique key, but other, **alternate**, record keys need not be unique.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Implementations of indexed files vary between vendors, although common implementations, such as C-ISAM and VSAM, are based on IBM's ISAM.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Other implementations are Record Management Services on OpenVMS and Enscribe on HPE NonStop (Tandem).
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Relative files, like indexed files, have a unique record key, but they do not have alternate keys.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] A relative record's key is its ordinal position; for example, the 10th record has a key of 10.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] This means that creating a record with a key of 5 may require the creation of (empty) preceding records.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Relative files also allow for both sequential and random access.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] A common non-standard extension is the **line sequential** organization, used to process text files.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Records in a file are terminated by a newline and may be of varying length.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Data items in COBOL are declared hierarchically through the use of level-numbers which indicate if a data item is part of another.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] An item with a higher level-number is subordinate to an item with a lower one.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Top-level data items, with a level-number of 1, are called **records**.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Items that have subordinate aggregate data are called **group items**; those that do not are called **elementary items**.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Level-numbers used to describe standard data items are between 1 and 49.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] In the above example, elementary item `num` and group item `the-date` are subordinate to the record `some-record`, while elementary items `the-year`, `the-month`, and `the-day` are part of the group item `the-date`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Subordinate items can be disambiguated with the `IN` (or `OF`) keyword.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The names `the-year`, `the-month`, and `the-day` are ambiguous by themselves, since more than one data item is defined with those names.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] To specify a particular data item, for instance one of the items contained within the `sale-date` group, the programmer would use `the-year IN sale-date` (or the equivalent `the-year OF sale-date`).
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] This syntax is similar to the "dot notation" supported by most contemporary languages.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] A level-number of 66 is used to declare a re-grouping of previously defined items, irrespective of how those items are structured.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] This data level, also referred to by the associated *`RENAMES` clause*, is rarely used and, circa 1988, was usually found in old programs.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Its ability to ignore the hierarchical and logical structure data meant its use was not recommended and many installations forbade its use.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] A 77 level-number indicates the item is stand-alone, and in such situations is equivalent to the level-number 01.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] An 88 level-number declares a **condition name** (a so-called 88-level) which is true when its parent data item contains one of the values specified in its `VALUE` clause.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] For example, the following code defines two 88-level condition-name items that are true or false depending on the current character data value of the `wage-type` data item.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] When the data item contains a value of `'H'`, the condition-name `wage-is-hourly` is true, whereas when it contains a value of `'S'` or `'Y'`, the condition-name `wage-is-yearly` is true.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] If the data item contains some other value, both of the condition-names are false.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Numeric data is converted between different representations and sizes silently and alphanumeric data can be placed in any data item that can be stored as a string, including numeric and group data.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] In contrast, object references and pointers may only be assigned from items of the same type and their values may be restricted to a certain type.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] A `PICTURE` (or `PIC`) clause is a string of characters, each of which represents a portion of the data item and what it may contain.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Some picture characters specify the type of the item and how many characters or digits it occupies in memory.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] For example, a `9` indicates a decimal digit, and an `S` indicates that the item is signed.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Other picture characters (called **insertion** and **editing** characters) specify how an item should be formatted.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Repeated characters can be specified more concisely by specifying a number in parentheses after a picture character; for example, `9(7)` is equivalent to `9999999`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Picture specifications containing only digit (`9`) and sign (`S`) characters define purely **numeric** data items, while picture specifications containing alphabetic (`A`) or alphanumeric (`X`) characters define **alphanumeric** data items.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The presence of other formatting characters define **edited numeric** or **edited alphanumeric** data items.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The `USAGE` clause declares the format in which data is stored.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Depending on the data type, it can either complement or be used instead of a `PICTURE` clause.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] While it can be used to declare pointers and object references, it is mostly geared towards specifying numeric types.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The report writer is a declarative facility for creating reports.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The programmer need only specify the report layout and the data required to produce it, freeing them from having to write code to handle things like page breaks, data formatting, and headings and footings.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Reports are associated with report files, which are files which may only be written to through report writer statements.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Each report is defined in the report section of the data division.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] A report is split into report groups which define the report's headings, footings and details.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Reports work around hierarchical **control breaks**.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Control breaks occur when a key variable changes it value; for example, when creating a report detailing customers' orders, a control break could occur when the program reaches a different customer's orders.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Four statements control the report writer: `INITIATE`, which prepares the report writer for printing; `GENERATE`, which prints a report group; `SUPPRESS`, which suppresses the printing of a report group; and `TERMINATE`, which terminates report processing.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Use of the Report Writer facility tends to vary considerably; some organizations use it extensively and some not at all.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] In addition, implementations of Report Writer ranged in quality, with those at the lower end sometimes using excessive amounts of memory at runtime.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The sections and paragraphs in the procedure division (collectively called procedures) can be used as labels and as simple subroutines.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Unlike in other divisions, paragraphs do not need to be in sections.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Execution goes down through the procedures of a program until it is terminated.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] To use procedures as subroutines, the `PERFORM` verb is used.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] A `PERFORM` statement somewhat resembles a procedure call in a newer languages in the sense that execution returns to the code following the `PERFORM` statement at the end of the called code; however, it does not provide a mechanism for parameter passing or for returning a result value.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] If a subroutine is invoked using a simple statement like `PERFORM subroutine`, then control returns at the end of the called procedure.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] However, `PERFORM` is unusual in that it may be used to call a range spanning a sequence of several adjacent procedures.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The output of this program will be: "A A B C".
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] `PERFORM` also differs from conventional procedure calls in that there is, at least traditionally, no notion of a call stack.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] As a consequence, nested invocations are possible (a sequence of code being `PERFORM`'ed may execute a `PERFORM` statement itself), but require extra care if parts of the same code are executed by both invocations.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The problem arises when the code in the inner invocation reaches the exit point of the outer invocation.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] More formally, if control passes through the exit point of a `PERFORM` invocation that was called earlier but has not yet completed, the COBOL 2002 standard stipulates that the behavior is undefined.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The reason is that COBOL, rather than a "return address", operates with what may be called a continuation address.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] When control flow reaches the end of any procedure, the continuation address is looked up and control is transferred to that address.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Before the program runs, the continuation address for every procedure is initialized to the start address of the procedure that comes next in the program text so that, if no `PERFORM` statements happen, control flows from top to bottom through the program.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] But when a `PERFORM` statement executes, it modifies the continuation address of the called procedure (or the last procedure of the called range, if `PERFORM THRU` was used), so that control will return to the call site at the end.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The original value is saved and is restored afterwards, but there is only one storage position.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] If two nested invocations operate on overlapping code, they may interfere which each other's management of the continuation address in several ways.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] One might expect that the output of this program would be "1 2 3 4 3": After displaying "2", the second `PERFORM` causes "3" and "4" to be displayed, and then the first invocation continues on with "3".
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] In traditional COBOL implementations, this is not the case.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Rather, the first `PERFORM` statement sets the continuation address at the end of `LABEL3` so that it will jump back to the call site inside `LABEL1`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The second `PERFORM` statement sets the return at the end of `LABEL4` but does not modify the continuation address of `LABEL3`, expecting it to be the default continuation.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Thus, when the inner invocation arrives at the end of `LABEL3`, it jumps back to the outer `PERFORM` statement, and the program stops having printed just "1 2 3".
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] On the other hand, in some COBOL implementations like the open-source TinyCOBOL compiler, the two `PERFORM` statements do not interfere with each other and the output is indeed "1 2 3 4 3".
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Therefore, the behavior in such cases is not only (perhaps) surprising, it is also not portable.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] A special consequence of this limitation is that `PERFORM` cannot be used to write recursive code.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] To write recursive routines, one must use a nested subprogram.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] One might expect that the output is "1 2 3 END END END", and in fact that is what some COBOL compilers will produce.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] But other compilers, like IBM COBOL, will produce code that prints "1 2 3 END END END END ..." and so on, printing "END" over and over in an endless loop.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Since there is limited space to store backup continuation addresses, the backups get overwritten in the course of recursive invocations, and all that can be restored is the jump back to `DISPLAY 'END'`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] COBOL 2014 has 47 statements (also called **verbs**), which can be grouped into the following broad categories: control flow, I/O, data manipulation and the report writer.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The report writer statements are covered in the report writer section.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] COBOL's conditional statements are `IF` and `EVALUATE`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] `EVALUATE` is a switch-like statement with the added capability of evaluating multiple values and conditions.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] This can be used to implement decision tables.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The `PERFORM` statement is used to define loops which are executed *until* a condition is true (not *while* true, which is more common in other languages).
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] It is also used to call procedures or ranges of procedures (see the procedures section for more details).
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] `CALL` and `INVOKE` call subprograms and methods, respectively.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The name of the subprogram/method is contained in a string which may be a literal or a data item.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Parameters can be passed by reference, by content (where a copy is passed by reference) or by value (but only if a prototype is available).
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] `CANCEL` unloads subprograms from memory.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] `GO TO` causes the program to jump to a specified procedure.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The `GOBACK` statement is a return statement and the `STOP` statement stops the program.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The `EXIT` statement has six different formats: it can be used as a return statement, a break statement, a continue statement, an end marker or to leave a procedure.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Exceptions are raised by a `RAISE` statement and caught with a handler, or **declarative**, defined in the `DECLARATIVES` portion of the procedure division.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Declaratives are sections beginning with a `USE` statement which specify the errors to handle.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] `RESUME` is used in a declarative to jump to the statement after the one that raised the exception or to a procedure outside the `DECLARATIVES`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Unlike other languages, uncaught exceptions may not terminate the program and the program can proceed unaffected.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] User interaction is done using `ACCEPT` and `DISPLAY`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Files and tables are sorted using `SORT` and the `MERGE` verb merges and sorts files.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The `RELEASE` verb provides records to sort and `RETURN` retrieves sorted records in order.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Some statements, such as `IF` and `READ`, may themselves contain statements.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Such statements may be terminated in two ways: by a period (**implicit termination**), which terminates *all* unterminated statements contained, or by a scope terminator, which terminates the nearest matching open statement.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Nested statements terminated with a period are a common source of bugs.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Here, the intent is to display `y` and `z` if condition `x` is true.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] However, `z` will be displayed whatever the value of `x` because the `IF` statement is terminated by an erroneous period after `DISPLAY y`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Another bug is a result of the dangling else problem, when two `IF` statements can associate with an `ELSE`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] In the above fragment, the `ELSE` associates with the `IF y` statement instead of the `IF x` statement, causing a bug.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Prior to the introduction of explicit scope terminators, preventing it would require `ELSE NEXT SENTENCE` to be placed after the inner `IF`.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The original (1960) COBOL specification supported the infamous `ALTER X TO PROCEED TO Y` statement, for which many compilers generated self-modifying code.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] `X` and `Y` are procedure labels, and the single `GO TO` statement in procedure `X` executed after such an `ALTER` statement means `GO TO Y` instead.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] Many compilers still support it, but it was deemed obsolete in the COBOL 1985 standard and deleted in 2002.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The `ALTER` statement was poorly regarded because it undermined "locality of context" and made a program's overall logic difficult to comprehend.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] When the now famous "Hello, World!" program example in *The C Programming Language* was first published in 1978 a similar mainframe COBOL program sample would have been submitted through JCL, very likely using a punch card reader, and 80 column punch cards.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The listing below, *with an empty `DATA DIVISION`*, was tested using Linux and the System/370 Hercules emulator running MVS 3.8J.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The JCL, written in July 2015, is derived from the Hercules tutorials and samples hosted by Jay Moseley.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] In keeping with COBOL programming of that era, HELLO, WORLD is displayed in all capital letters.
[src:cobol/cobol-p02] The associated compiler listing generated over four pages of technical detail and job run information, for the single line of output from the 14 lines of COBOL.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] In the 1970s, adoption of the structured programming paradigm was becoming increasingly widespread.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] In a published dissent to Dijkstra's remarks, the computer scientist Howard E.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Tompkins claimed that unstructured COBOL tended to be "written by programmers that have never had the benefit of structured COBOL taught well", arguing that the issue was primarily one of training.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] One cause of spaghetti code was the `GO TO` statement.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Attempts to remove `GO TO`s from COBOL code, however, resulted in convoluted programs and reduced code quality.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] `GO TO`s were largely replaced by the `PERFORM` statement and procedures, which promoted modular programming and gave easy access to powerful looping facilities.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] However, `PERFORM` could be used only with procedures so loop bodies were not located where they were used, making programs harder to understand.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Since the adoption of the 1985 standard, the need for `GO TO` has been completely obliviated by rich features of the `PERFORM` verb; however, `GO TO` remains for backwards compatibility, as it does in many other languages.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] COBOL programs were infamous for being monolithic and lacking modularization.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] COBOL code could be modularized only through procedures, which were found to be inadequate for large systems.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Otherwise, it was required to `CALL` separately compiled programs for modularity.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] It was impossible to restrict access to data until the COBOL-85 standard, meaning a procedure could access and modify *any* data item.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Furthermore, there was no way to pass parameters to a procedure, an omission Jean Sammet regarded as the committee's biggest mistake..
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] This problem was removed in the COBOL-85 standard with the introduction of the nested subprogram which allowed for modularity and locally isolated data items.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Another complication stemmed from the ability to `PERFORM THRU` a specified sequence of procedures.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] This meant that control could jump to and return from any procedure, creating convoluted control flow and permitting a programmer to break the single-entry single-exit rule.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] This situation improved as COBOL adopted more features.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] COBOL-74 added subprograms, giving programmers the ability to control the data each part of the program could access.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] COBOL-85 then added nested subprograms, allowing programmers to hide subprograms.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Further control over data and code came in 2002 when object-oriented programming, user-defined functions and user-defined data types were included.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Nevertheless, much important legacy COBOL software uses unstructured code, which has become practically unmaintainable.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] It can be too risky and costly to modify even a simple section of code, since it may be used from unknown places in unknown ways.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] COBOL was intended to be a highly portable, "common" language.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] However, by 2001, around 300 dialects had been created.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] One source of dialects was the standard itself: the 1974 standard was composed of one mandatory nucleus and eleven functional modules, each containing two or three levels of support.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] This permitted 104,976 possible variants.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] COBOL-85 was not fully compatible with earlier versions, and its development was controversial.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Brophy, the CIO of Travelers Insurance, spearheaded an effort to inform COBOL users of the heavy reprogramming costs of implementing the new standard.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] As a result, the ANSI COBOL Committee received more than 2,200 letters from the public, mostly negative, requiring the committee to make changes.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] On the other hand, conversion to COBOL-85 was thought to increase productivity in future years, thus justifying the conversion costs.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] COBOL syntax has often been criticized for its verbosity.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Proponents say that this was intended to make the code self-documenting, easing program maintenance.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] COBOL was also intended to be easy for programmers to learn and use, while still being readable to non-technical staff such as managers.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] The desire for readability led to the use of English-like syntax and structural elements, such as nouns, verbs, clauses, sentences, sections, and divisions.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Yet by 1984, maintainers of COBOL programs were struggling to deal with "incomprehensible" code and the main changes in COBOL-85 were there to help ease maintenance.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Jean Sammet, a short-range committee member, noted that "little attempt was made to cater to the professional programmer, in fact people whose main interest is programming tend to be very unhappy with COBOL" which she attributed to COBOL's verbose syntax.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Later, COBOL suffered from a shortage of material covering it; it took until 1963 for introductory books to appear (with Richard D.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Irwin publishing a college textbook on COBOL in 1966).
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Donald Nelson, chair of the CODASYL COBOL committee, said in 1984 that "academics ... hate COBOL" and that computer science graduates "had 'hate COBOL' drilled into them".
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] By the mid-1980s, there was also significant condescension towards COBOL in the business community from users of other languages, for example FORTRAN or assembler, implying that COBOL could be used only for non-challenging problems.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] In 2003, COBOL featured in 80% of information systems curricula in the United States, the same proportion as C++ and Java.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Ten years later, a poll by Micro Focus found that 20% of university academics thought COBOL was outdated or dead and that 55% believed their students thought COBOL was outdated or dead.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] The same poll also found that only 25% of academics had COBOL programming on their curriculum even though 60% thought they should teach it.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Doubts have been raised about the competence of the standards committee.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] COBOL standards have repeatedly suffered from delays: COBOL-85 arrived five years later than hoped, COBOL 2002 was five years late, and COBOL 2014 was six years late.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] To combat delays, the standard committee allowed the creation of optional addenda which would add features more quickly than by waiting for the next standard revision.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] However, some committee members raised concerns about incompatibilities between implementations and frequent modifications of the standard.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] COBOL's data structures influenced subsequent programming languages.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Its record and file structure influenced PL/I and Pascal, and the `REDEFINES` clause was a predecessor to Pascal's variant records.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Explicit file structure definitions preceded the development of database management systems and aggregated data was a significant advance over Fortran's arrays.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] `PICTURE` data declarations were incorporated into PL/I, with minor changes.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] COBOL's `COPY` facility, although considered "primitive", influenced the development of include directives.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] The focus on portability and standardization meant programs written in COBOL could be portable and facilitated the spread of the language to a wide variety of hardware platforms and operating systems.
[src:cobol/cobol-p03] Additionally, the well-defined division structure restricts the definition of external references to the Environment Division, which simplifies platform changes in particular.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] A "**Hello, world**" program is usually a simple computer program that displays on the screen (often the console) a message similar to "Hello, world".
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] A small piece of code in most general-purpose programming languages, this program is used to illustrate a language's basic syntax.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] Such a program is often the first written by a student of a new programming language, but it can also be used as a sanity check to ensure that the computer software intended to compile or run source code is correctly installed, and that its operator understands how to use it.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] While several small test programs have existed since the development of programmable computers, the tradition of using the phrase "Hello, world" as a test message was influenced by an example program in the 1978 book *The C Programming Language*, with likely earlier use in BCPL.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] In the above example, the main( ) function defines where the program should start executing.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] The function body consists of a single statement, a call to the printf() function, which stands for "*print f*ormatted"; it outputs to the console whatever is passed to it as the parameter, in this case the string "hello, world".
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] The program above prints *hello, world!* on the terminal, including a newline character.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] The phrase is divided into multiple variables because in B, a character constant is limited to four ASCII characters.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] The previous example in the tutorial printed *hi!* on the terminal, and the phrase *hello, world!* was introduced as a slightly longer greeting that required several character constants for its expression.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] The Jargon File reports that "hello, world!" instead originated in 1967 with the language BCPL.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] Outside computing, use of the exact phrase began over a decade prior; it was the catchphrase of New York radio disc jockey William B.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] "Hello, world" programs vary in complexity between different languages.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] In some languages, particularly scripting languages, the "Hello, world" program can be written as one statement, while in others (more so many low-level languages) many more statements can be required.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] For example, in Python, to print the string *Hello, world* followed by a newline, one only needs to write `print("Hello, world")`.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] In contrast, the equivalent code in C++ requires the import of the C++ standard library, the declaration of an entry point (main function), and a call to print a line of text to the standard output stream.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] The phrase "Hello, world" has seen various deviations in casing and punctuation, such as the presence or absence of the comma or exclamation mark.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] Some devices limit the format to specific variations, such as all-capitalized versions on systems that support only capital letters, while some esoteric programming languages may have to print a slightly modified string.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] Other human languages have been used as the output; for example, a tutorial for the Go language emitted both English and Chinese or Japanese characters, demonstrating the language's built-in Unicode support.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] Another notable example is the Rust language, whose management system automatically inserts a "Hello, World" program when creating new projects.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] Some languages change the function of the "Hello, world" program while maintaining the spirit of demonstrating a simple example.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] Languages otherwise able to print "Hello, world" (assembly language, C, VHDL) may also be used in embedded systems, where text output is either difficult (requiring added components or communication with another computer) or nonexistent.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] For devices such as microcontrollers, field-programmable gate arrays, and complex programmable logic devices (CPLDs), "Hello, world" may thus be substituted with a blinking light-emitting diode (LED), which demonstrates timing and interaction between components.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] The Debian and Ubuntu Linux distributions provide the "Hello, world" program through their software package manager systems, which can be invoked with the command *hello*.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] It serves as a sanity check and a simple example of installing a software package.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] For developers, it provides an example of creating a .deb package, either traditionally or using *debhelper*, and the version of hello used, GNU Hello, serves as an example of writing a GNU program.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] Variations of the "Hello, world" program that produce a graphical output (as opposed to text output) have also been shown.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] Sun demonstrated a "Hello, world" program in Java based on scalable vector graphics, and the XL programming language features a spinning Earth "Hello, world" using 3D computer graphics.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] Mark Guzdial and Elliot Soloway have suggested that the "hello, world" test message may be outdated now that graphics and sound can be manipulated as easily as text.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] In computer graphics, rendering a triangle—the "Hello Triangle"—is sometimes used as an introductory example for graphics libraries.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] "Time to hello world" (TTHW) is the time it takes to author a "Hello, world" program in a given programming language.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] This is one measure of a programming language's ease of use.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] Since the program is meant as an introduction for people unfamiliar with the language, a more complex "Hello, world" program may indicate that the programming language is less approachable.
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] For instance, the first publicly known "Hello, world" program in Malbolge (which actually output "HEllO WORld") took two years to be announced, and it was produced not by a human but by a code generator written in Common Lisp .
[src:cobol/hello-world-program] The concept has been extended beyond programming languages to APIs, as a measure of how simple it is for a new developer to get a basic example working; a shorter time indicates an easier API for developers to adopt.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The **.NET Framework** (pronounced "*dot net*") is a proprietary software framework developed by Microsoft that runs primarily on Microsoft Windows.
[src:cobol/net-framework] It was the predominant implementation of the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) until being superseded by the cross-platform .NET project.
[src:cobol/net-framework] It includes a large class library called Framework Class Library (FCL) and provides language interoperability (each language can use code written in other languages) across several programming languages.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Programs written for .NET Framework execute in a software environment (in contrast to a hardware environment) named the Common Language Runtime (CLR).
[src:cobol/net-framework] The CLR is an application virtual machine that provides services such as security, memory management, and exception handling.
[src:cobol/net-framework] As such, computer code written using .NET Framework is called "managed code".
[src:cobol/net-framework] FCL and CLR together constitute the .NET Framework.
[src:cobol/net-framework] FCL provides the user interface, data access, database connectivity, cryptography, web application development, numeric algorithms, and network communications.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Programmers produce software by combining their source code with the .NET Framework and other libraries.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The framework is intended to be used by most new applications created for the Windows platform.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Microsoft also produces an integrated development environment for .NET software called Visual Studio.
[src:cobol/net-framework] .NET Framework began as proprietary software, although the firm worked to standardize the software stack almost immediately, even before its first release.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Despite the standardization efforts, developers, mainly those in the free and open-source software communities, expressed their unease with the selected terms and the prospects of any free and open-source implementation, especially regarding software patents.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Since then, Microsoft has changed .NET development to more closely follow a contemporary model of a community-developed software project, including issuing an update to its patent promising to address the concerns.
[src:cobol/net-framework] In April 2019, Microsoft released .NET Framework 4.8, the last major version of the framework as a proprietary offering, followed by .NET Framework 4.8.1 in August 2022.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Only monthly security and reliability bug fixes to that version have been released since then.
[src:cobol/net-framework] No further changes to that version are planned.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The .NET Framework will continue to be included with future releases of Windows and continue to receive security updates, with no plans to remove it as of July 2025.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Microsoft began developing .NET Framework in the late 1990s, originally under the name of Next Generation Windows Services (NGWS), as part of the Microsoft .NET strategy.
[src:cobol/net-framework] By early 2000, the first beta versions of .NET 1.0 were released.
[src:cobol/net-framework] In August 2000, Microsoft and Intel worked to standardize Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) and C#.
[src:cobol/net-framework] By December 2001, both were ratified as ECMA standards.
[src:cobol/net-framework] International Organization for Standardization (ISO) followed in April 2003.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The current version of ISO standards are ISO/IEC 23271:2012 and ISO/IEC 23270:2006.
[src:cobol/net-framework] While Microsoft and their partners hold patents for CLI and C#, ECMA and ISO require that all patents essential to implementation be made available under "reasonable and non-discriminatory terms".
[src:cobol/net-framework] The firms agreed to meet these terms, and to make the patents available royalty-free.
[src:cobol/net-framework] However, this did not apply to the part of the .NET Framework not covered by ECMA-ISO standards, which included Windows Forms, ADO.NET, and ASP.NET.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Patents that Microsoft holds in these areas may have deterred non-Microsoft implementations of the full framework.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Windows Vista is the first client version of Windows that integrated the .NET Framework.
[src:cobol/net-framework] On October 3, 2007, Microsoft announced that the source code for .NET Framework 3.5 libraries was to become available under the Microsoft Reference Source License (Ms-RSL).
[src:cobol/net-framework] The source code repository became available online on January 16, 2008, and included BCL, ASP.NET, ADO.NET, Windows Forms, WPF, and XML.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Scott Guthrie of Microsoft promised that LINQ, WCF, and WF libraries were being added.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The .NET Compact Framework and .NET Micro Framework variants of the .NET Framework provided support for other Microsoft platforms such as Windows Mobile, Windows CE and other resource-constrained embedded devices.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Silverlight provided support for web browsers via plug-ins.
[src:cobol/net-framework] In November 2014, Microsoft also produced an update to its patent grants, which further extends the scope beyond its prior pledges.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Prior projects like Mono existed in a legal gray area because Microsoft's earlier grants applied only to the technology in "covered specifications", including strictly the 4th editions each of ECMA-334 and ECMA-335.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The new patent promise, however, places no ceiling on the specification version, and even extends to any .NET runtime technologies documented on MSDN that have not been formally specified by the ECMA group, if a project chooses to implement them.
[src:cobol/net-framework] This allows Mono and other projects to maintain feature parity with modern .NET features that have been introduced since the 4th edition was published all without being at risk of patent litigation over the implementation of those features.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The new grant does maintain the restriction that any implementation must maintain minimum compliance with the mandatory parts of the CLI specification.
[src:cobol/net-framework] On March 31, 2016, Microsoft announced at Microsoft Build that they will completely relicense Mono under an MIT License even in scenarios where formerly a commercial license was needed.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Microsoft also supplemented its prior patent promise for Mono, stating that they will not assert any "applicable patents" against parties that are "using, selling, offering for sale, importing, or distributing Mono." It was announced that the Mono Project was contributed to the .NET Foundation.
[src:cobol/net-framework] These developments followed the acquisition of Xamarin, which began in February 2016 and was finished on March 18, 2016.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Microsoft's press release highlights that the cross-platform commitment now allows for a fully open-source, modern server-side .NET stack.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Microsoft released the source code for WPF, Windows Forms and WinUI on December 4, 2018.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) provides a language-neutral platform for application development and execution.
[src:cobol/net-framework] By implementing the core aspects of .NET Framework within the scope of CLI, these functions will not be tied to one language but will be available across the many languages supported by the framework.
[src:cobol/net-framework] .NET Framework includes the Common Language Runtime (CLR).
[src:cobol/net-framework] It serves as the execution engine of .NET Framework and offers many services such as memory management, type safety, exception handling, garbage collection, security and thread management.
[src:cobol/net-framework] All programs written for .NET Framework are executed by the CLR.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Programs written for .NET Framework are compiled into Common Intermediate Language code (CIL), as opposed to being directly compiled into machine code.
[src:cobol/net-framework] During execution, an architecture-specific just-in-time compiler (JIT) turns the CIL code into machine code.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Compiled CLI code is stored in CLI assemblies.
[src:cobol/net-framework] As mandated by the specification, assemblies are stored in Portable Executable (PE) file format, common on Windows platform for all *dynamic-link library* (DLL) and *executable* EXE files.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Each assembly consists of one or more files, one of which must contain a manifest bearing the metadata for the assembly.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The complete name of an assembly (not to be confused with the file name on disk) contains its simple text name, version number, culture, and public key token.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Assemblies are considered equivalent if they share the same complete name.
[src:cobol/net-framework] A private key can also be used by the creator of the assembly for strong naming.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The public key token determines the real-world identity of the assembly's signer.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Only those knowing their private key (of the double-key cryptography system) can sign assemblies that have the same strong name as a prior version assembly.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Strong naming is required to add assemblies to Global Assembly Cache.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Starting with Visual Studio 2015, .NET Native compilation technology allows for the compilation of .NET code of Universal Windows Platform apps directly to machine code rather than CIL code, but the app must be written in either C# or Visual Basic.NET.
[src:cobol/net-framework] .NET Framework includes an implementation of the CLI foundational Standard Libraries.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The .NET Framework Class Library (FCL) is organized in a hierarchy of namespaces.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Most of the built-in application programming interfaces (APIs) are part of either `System.*` or `Microsoft.*` namespaces.
[src:cobol/net-framework] These class libraries implement many common functions, such as file reading and writing, graphic rendering, database interaction, and XML document manipulation.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The class libraries are available for all CLI compliant languages.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The FCL implements the CLI Base Class Library (BCL) and other class libraries—some are specified by CLI and others are Microsoft specific.
[src:cobol/net-framework] BCL includes a small subset of the entire class library and is the core set of classes that serve as the basic API of CLR.
[src:cobol/net-framework] For .NET Framework most classes considered being part of BCL reside in `mscorlib.dll`, `System.dll` and `System.Core.dll`.
[src:cobol/net-framework] BCL classes are available in .NET Framework as well as in CLI's alternative implementations, including .NET Compact Framework, Microsoft Silverlight, .NET Core and Mono.
[src:cobol/net-framework] FCL refers to the entire class library that ships with .NET Framework.
[src:cobol/net-framework] It includes BCL, an expanded set of libraries, including Windows Forms, ASP.NET, and Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), and also extensions to the base class libraries ADO.NET, Language Integrated Query (LINQ), Windows Communication Foundation (WCF), and Workflow Foundation (WF).
[src:cobol/net-framework] FCL is much larger in scope than standard libraries for languages like C++, and comparable in scope to standard libraries of Java.
[src:cobol/net-framework] With the introduction of alternative CLI's implementations (e.g., Silverlight), Microsoft introduced the concept of Portable Class Libraries (PCL) allowing a consuming library to run on more than one implementation.
[src:cobol/net-framework] With the further proliferation of implementations, the PCL approach failed to scale (PCLs are defined intersections of API surface between two or more implementations).
[src:cobol/net-framework] As the next evolutionary step of PCL, the .NET Standard Library was created retroactively based on the `System.Runtime.dll` based APIs found in UWP and Silverlight.
[src:cobol/net-framework] New CLI's implementations are encouraged to implement a version of the Standard Library allowing them to run existent third-party libraries with no need of creating new versions of them.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The .NET Standard Library allows an independent evolution of the library and app model layers within the .NET architecture.
[src:cobol/net-framework] NuGet is the package manager for all .NET platforms.
[src:cobol/net-framework] It is used to retrieve third-party libraries into a .NET project with a global library feed at NuGet.org.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Private feeds can be maintained separately, e.g., by a build server or a file system directory.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Microsoft introduced C++/CLI in Visual Studio 2005, which is a language and means of compiling Visual C++ programs to run within the .NET Framework.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Some parts of the C++ program still run within an unmanaged Visual C++ Runtime, while specially modified parts are translated into CIL code and run with the .NET Framework's CLR.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Assemblies compiled using the C++/CLI compiler are termed mixed-mode assemblies since they contain native and managed code in the same DLL.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Such assemblies are more complex to reverse engineer since .NET decompilers such as .NET Reflector reveal only the managed code.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Because computer systems commonly require interaction between newer and older applications, .NET Framework provides means to access functions implemented in newer and older programs that execute outside .NET environment.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Access to Component Object Model (COM) components is provided in `System.Runtime.InteropServices` and `System.EnterpriseServices` namespaces of the framework.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Access to other functions is via Platform Invocation Services (P/Invoke).
[src:cobol/net-framework] Access to .NET functions from native applications is via the reverse P/Invoke function.
[src:cobol/net-framework] .NET Framework introduces a Common Type System (CTS) that defines all possible data types and programming constructs supported by CLR and how they may or may not interact conforming to CLI specifications.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Because of this feature, .NET Framework supports the exchange of types and object instances between libraries and applications written using any conforming CLI language.
[src:cobol/net-framework] CTS and the CLR used in .NET Framework also enforce type safety.
[src:cobol/net-framework] This prevents ill-defined casts, wrong method invocations, and memory size issues when accessing an object.
[src:cobol/net-framework] This also makes most CLI languages statically typed (with or without type inference).
[src:cobol/net-framework] However, starting with .NET Framework 4.0, the Dynamic Language Runtime extended the CLR, allowing dynamically typed languages to be implemented atop the CLI.
[src:cobol/net-framework] While Microsoft has never implemented the full framework on any system except Microsoft Windows, it has engineered the framework to be cross-platform, and implementations are available for other operating systems (see Silverlight and § Alternative implementations).
[src:cobol/net-framework] Microsoft submitted the specifications for CLI (which includes the Base Class Libraries, CTS, and CIL), C#, and C++/CLI to both Ecma International (ECMA) and International Organization for Standardization (ISO), making them available as official standards.
[src:cobol/net-framework] This makes it possible for third parties to create compatible implementations of the framework and its languages on other platforms.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Core cross-platform .NET (formerly .NET Core) is officially available also for many Linux distributions and macOS.
[src:cobol/net-framework] .NET Framework has its own security mechanism with two general features: Code Access Security (CAS), and validation and verification.
[src:cobol/net-framework] CAS is based on evidence that is associated with a specific assembly.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Typically, the evidence is the source of the assembly (whether it is installed on the local machine or has been downloaded from the Internet).
[src:cobol/net-framework] CAS uses evidence to determine the permissions granted to the code.
[src:cobol/net-framework] When calling code demands that it be granted a specific permission, CLR performs a call stack walk checking every assembly of each method in the call stack for the required permission; if any assembly is not granted the permission, it will throw a security exception.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Managed CIL bytecode is easier to reverse-engineer than native code, unless obfuscated. .NET decompiler programs enable developers with no reverse-engineering skills to view the source code behind unobfuscated .NET assemblies.
[src:cobol/net-framework] In contrast, apps compiled from native machine code are much harder to reverse-engineer, and source code is almost never produced successfully, mainly because of compiler optimizations and lack of reflection.
[src:cobol/net-framework] This creates concerns in the business community over the possible loss of trade secrets and the bypassing of license control mechanisms.
[src:cobol/net-framework] To mitigate this, Microsoft has included Dotfuscator Community Edition with Visual Studio .NET since 2002.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Third-party obfuscation tools are also available from vendors such as VMware, V.i.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Method-level encryption tools for .NET code are available from vendors such as SafeNet.
[src:cobol/net-framework] CLR frees the developer from the burden of managing memory (allocating and freeing up when done); it handles memory management itself by detecting when memory can be safely freed.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Instantiations of .NET types (objects) are allocated from the managed heap; a pool of memory managed by CLR.
[src:cobol/net-framework] As long as a reference to an object exists, which may be either direct, or via a graph of objects, the object is considered to be in use.
[src:cobol/net-framework] When no reference to an object exists, and it cannot be reached or used, it becomes garbage, eligible for collection.
[src:cobol/net-framework] .NET Framework includes a garbage collector (GC) which runs periodically, on a separate thread from the application's thread, that enumerates all the unusable objects and reclaims the memory allocated to them.
[src:cobol/net-framework] It is a non-deterministic, compacting, mark-and-sweep garbage collector.
[src:cobol/net-framework] GC runs only when a set amount of memory has been used or there is enough pressure for memory on the system.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Since it is not guaranteed when the conditions to reclaim memory are reached, GC runs are non-deterministic.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Each .NET application has a set of roots, which are pointers to objects on the managed heap (*managed objects*).
[src:cobol/net-framework] These include references to static objects, objects defined as local variables or method parameters currently in scope, and objects referred to by CPU registers.
[src:cobol/net-framework] When GC runs, it pauses the application and then, for each object referred to in the root, it recursively enumerates all the objects reachable from the root objects and marks them as reachable.
[src:cobol/net-framework] It uses CLI metadata and reflection to discover the objects encapsulated by an object, and then recursively walk them.
[src:cobol/net-framework] It then enumerates all the objects on the heap (which were initially allocated contiguously) using reflection.
[src:cobol/net-framework] All objects not marked as reachable are garbage.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Since the memory held by garbage is of no consequence, it is considered free space.
[src:cobol/net-framework] However, this leaves chunks of free space between objects which were initially contiguous.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The objects are then *compacted* together to make free space on the managed heap contiguous again.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Any reference to an object invalidated by moving the object is updated by GC to reflect the new location.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The application is resumed after garbage collection ends.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The latest version of .NET framework uses concurrent garbage collection along with user code, making pauses unnoticeable, because it is done in the background.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The garbage collector used by .NET Framework is also *generational*.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Newly created objects are tagged *Generation 0*.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Objects that survive one garbage collection are tagged *Generation 1*.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Generation 1 objects that survive another collection are *Generation 2*.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The framework uses up to Generation 2 objects.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Higher generation objects are garbage collected less often than lower generation objects.
[src:cobol/net-framework] This raises the efficiency of garbage collection, as older objects tend to have longer lifetimes than newer objects.
[src:cobol/net-framework] By ignoring older objects in most collection runs, fewer checks and compaction operations are needed in total.
[src:cobol/net-framework] When an application is first launched, the .NET Framework compiles the CIL code into executable code using its just-in-time compiler, and caches the executable program into the .NET Native Image Cache.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Due to caching, the application launches faster for subsequent launches, although the first launch is usually slower.
[src:cobol/net-framework] To speed up the first launch, developers may use the Native Image Generator utility to manually ahead-of-time compile and cache any .NET application.
[src:cobol/net-framework] The garbage collector, which is integrated into the environment, can introduce unanticipated delays of execution over which the developer has little direct control.
[src:cobol/net-framework] .NET Framework provides support for calling Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE) via managed code from April 2014 in Visual Studio 2013 Update 2.
[src:cobol/net-framework] However, Mono has provided support for SIMD Extensions as of version 2.2 within the Mono.Simd namespace in 2009.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Mono's lead developer Miguel de Icaza has expressed hope that this SIMD support will be adopted by CLR's ECMA standard.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Streaming SIMD Extensions have been available in x86 CPUs since the introduction of the Pentium III.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Some other architectures such as ARM and MIPS also have SIMD extensions.
[src:cobol/net-framework] In case the CPU lacks support for those extensions, the instructions are simulated in software.
[src:cobol/net-framework] .NET Framework was the predominant implementation of CLI, until the release of .NET.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Other implementations for parts of the framework exist.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Although the runtime engine is described by an ECMA-ISO specification, other implementations of it may be encumbered by patent issues; ISO standards may include the disclaimer, "Attention is drawn to the possibility that some of the elements of this document may be the subject of patent rights.
[src:cobol/net-framework] ISO shall not be held responsible for identifying any or all such patent rights." It is harder to develop alternatives to FCL, which is not described by an open standard and may be subject to copyright restrictions.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Also, parts of FCL have Windows-specific functions and behavior, so implementation on non-Windows platforms can be problematic.
[src:cobol/net-framework] Some alternative implementations of parts of the framework are listed here.
